Still cranking after over 1 year of consistent use. This is my longest lived shredder. Usually I kill shredders within the year so I view them as effectively disposable. product_title: Kensington Bluetooth Presentation
review_headline: A mixed bag, but generally good.
review_body:
There is a lot to like about this presentation controller, and a few things that will drive you nuts! Let's deal with the positives first.

It's a nice, sleek little unit, and it fits nicely in the hand while giving a presentation. It isn't burdened down with a bunch of buttons--just a four-way rocker for next slide (right), previous slide (left), laser pointer on (top), and blacken screen (down). I like that simplicity. On my Mac and Windows laptops, it works from 10 to 15 feet away, which is all I need. It comes with a nice carrying case and a recharging cable. And left to just that, I'd give the unit five stars. Here's why I knocked off a star:

A few reviewers have complained that the unit won't hold power--that you have to charge the unit just before you use it or it will be dead when you start your presentation. That's not really the case, but I understand how they came to that conclusion. The unit does not have an LED to let you know it is turned on. There is a small LED that flashes when you turn the unit on, and again, more quickly, when you turn the unit off. Until you get the hang of the flashing frequencies, you might very well think you had turned the unit off when you hadn't. That's a bit of a pain.

The second problem is with pairing. I had no real problem with my Windows laptop, but my Mac (running OS 10.10 'Yosemite'), paired it as an 'unknown keyboard'. A search through Kensington's FAQs uncovered a note to restart the Mac after pairing, at which time it would reappear in the Bluetooth device list as a mouse, and that turned out to be the case. But, that's another pain.

So, when I travel with this controller, I bring along a little cheat sheet with the details on pairing to both Mac and Windows, in case I end up using someone else's laptop for my presentation, and how to verify that the unit has been turned off. Perhaps Apple has spoiled me, but I don't feel like I should have to do that.

One final minor annoyance: The recharging port for the unit, a micro USB port, is in the midsection of the unit, and the top and bottom sections slide together while presenting and cover up the port. That's nice when it comes to protecting the port from dirt and grime, but if you forget that you have to slide the top and bottom apart a bit to expose the port, it can take a few minutes to find it.

Even with all that said, I think this is still a better Bluetooth presenter than most of the other units out there, and it is a good value for the money. Note that it does not include a Bluetooth dongle for the laptop on which it is used, so the laptop will either have to support Bluetooth natively, or you will need to buy a Bluetooth dongle separately and install its drivers on your laptop. And note that the controller won't work with phones or tablets, since it has to emulate a mouse. Subject to the hassles noted above, I can recommend it for Windows and Mac use.l minor annoyance: The recharging port for the unit, a micro USB port, is in the midsection of the unit, and the top and bottom sections slide together while presenting and cover up the port. That's nice when it comes to protecting the port from dirt and grime, but if you forget that you have to slide the top and bottom apart a bit to expose the port, it can take a few minutes to find it.

Even with all that said, I think this is still a better Bluetooth presenter than most of the other units out there, and it is a good value for the money. Note that it does not include a Bluetooth dongle for the laptop on which it is used, so the laptop will either have to support Bluetooth natively, or you will need to buy a Bluetooth dongle separately and install its drivers on your laptop. And note that the controller won't work with phones or tablets, since it has to emulate a mouse. Subject to the hassles noted above, I can recommend it for Windows and Mac use.

product_title: elago L4 Stand - [Desk Organization][Prevents Bad Posture][Natural Heat Sink] - for Laptop Computers
review_headline: [REVIEW] Elago L4 stand for laptop computers (silver). A solid, well-designed laptop stand. Definitely recommended!
review_body:
[REVIEW] Elago L4 stand for laptop computers (silver). A solid, well-designed laptop stand. Definitely recommended!

My primary computer has been a Mac with either a desktop or mini-tower form factor, a large display and old-school Matias Tactile Pro clickety-clack keyboard and Logitech cordless optical mouse. Over the summer, I replaced my main system - a Mac Pro with a 24” display - with a Macbook Pro. With the exception of the keyboard and mouse, the Mac Pro and all of its affiliated hardware was moved to a different location. The last time I used a laptop as a primary computer was as an undergraduate student in the early 90s. No doubt, there would be a transition. I kept my keyboard and mouse because I intended to use them with the my Macbook Pro during and/or after the transition. It didn’t work out quite as well as I planned and I ended up putting them in storage temporarily.

Although I love my new Macbook Pro, I found I missed a large display, keyboard and mouse. Since both of my older brothers use their Macbook Pro laptops with external displays, I decided to follow suit. I replaced the old 24” display with a nice 27” model, planted it on my desk and moved the laptop to the side. What a difference! Although I love the display on my laptop, my eyes liked the extra screen real estate and my fingers were grateful to machine-gun tap on my old keyboard again. The only thing left to do was better situate my laptop, especially since I used its display in conjunction with the new one.

Enter a laptop stand.

Both of my brothers have a Rain Design mStand laptop stand. they are very happy with its performance. That alone made it worth a looksie. The mStand is a very nice stand! Definitely a solid, well-made, piece of equipment. The mStand would have done the job and I’d’ve bought it if I hadn’t come upon the Elago L4 laptop stand. But, I came upon the L4 while browsing the products I saw on amazon.com and it wouldbe just right.

Review Summary:

This summary is for those of you who aren’t inclined to read the review in its entirety. The Elago L4 stand for laptop computers (silver) is a very nice laptop stand. Is it perfect? No. It has a few minor flaws that are either ignored or easily fixed. Does it have some nice features? Absolutely. Will the L4 do its job? Without a doubt. Despite the minor flaws, the L4 is a nicely finished, well made, sturdy laptop stand. Although I’ve only had the L4 for a few days, I’m pleased by how well it suits my workflow. I definitely recommend it. Read on for the full review with all the details!

Full Review:

I was searching for just the right stand for my Macbook Pro and narrowed my choices down to the Rain Design mStand and the Elago L4 stand for laptop computers. In looking at these stands, I felt I couldn’t go wrong with either. Both stands are made out of a solid piece of aluminum. They have a lip that prevents laptops from slipping off them. I can confirm the quality of the Rain Design mStand since both of my brothers have one and adore it. I gave it a looksie and can say it’s a great piece of equipment. Why did I choose the Elago L4 over it? Design. Although I know the mStand is a solid, well made piece of equipment, I preferred the design of the L4. It has a huge open space beneath it and an open back, which I knew would suit the way I have my computer hardware set up on my desk. The space beneath the stand is a perfect location for my MPow USB 3.0 hub or anything else I just happen to be using with my Macbook Pro.

Inspecting the Elago L4 stand for laptop computers:

I opened the box of the L4 stand and was a bit disappointed. Surprised to hear me say this? Don’t be. Elago didn’t include any protective packaging in the box. Admittedly, the stand is a solid piece of aluminum. It isn’t the kind of product one would expect to get damaged easily. Nonetheless, inthis day and age of poorly packaged shipping boxes and horrendous handling by small package carriers, additional protective packaging in a product’s box is a necessity. Even for something as sturdy as an aluminum laptop stand. And, for the record, Amazon.com included a couple of heavy plastic shovel handles and very little protective stuffing in the shipping box that contained the L4 stand. It was clear they’d been bouncing around the entire time the box was in transit from the Amazon warehouse to my office. Fortunately, none of this had any impact on the L$ stand, which arrived in mint condition.

Despite the lack of protective packaging, Elago packs the L4 in a nice looking box with a handle. The handle on the box came in handy at the end of the day when I carried the L4 to my car and my apartment. But, being on the impatient side, I decided to open the L4’s box at my office to give it a looksie. The L4 is heavier than I anticipated! Based on some of the other reviews, I expected it to be very lightweight aluminum. While the stand isn’t incredibly heavy, it is not lightweight either. The L4 has a solid, sturdy feel to it and is easily heavy enough to keep from slip-sliding on a desk and that’s without the extra weight of a laptop.

Many of the products I sell are produced using the method(s) used to make products like the L4 stand. That means, when I look at an item like the L4 stand, I have high expectations when it comes to the workmanship. Elago did a very good job with the L4 stand. I didn’t find any burrs. No sharp edges. The stand isn’t cockeyed. Overall, it looks like the L4 itself was made with care. However, there is something to be desired with the protective pads included on the stand. The pads aren’t particularly good and don’t do justice to what is otherwise a nice product.

The L4 is supposed to have a few pads on the platform area upon which you place your laptop but whoever was supposed to stick themon them forgot to do so. The pads weren’t in the box either. As a result, it is possible the bottom of a computer could get scratched when it is placed on or removed from the L4. Could is the operative word. The pad on the lip of the L4 is thin and barely sufficient to protect the front of a laptop from scratching. The pads on the feet of the stand are definitely inadequate and careless sliding of the L4 could result in a scratched desktop surface. You may think I’m being a bit nit-picky about the pads but I think it’s reasonable criticism. The missing and poor pads could result in damage to your laptop and diminishes what is otherwise a fine product.

A nice laptop can be a very expensive purchase and nobody wants to see it get scratched because the manufacturer of the stand you’re using skimped on the protective pads. I nearly returned the L4, not because the lack of and poor pads presented a problem for my Macbook Pro, but on principal. The stand isn’t cheap and I expected better from the manufacturer based on the pictures and reviews. I decided to keep the L4 because the problem is a non-issue in my particular situation and I love the stand itself.

My Macbook Pro has a Speck SeeThru Satin shell case which protects it from scratches and similar damage. So, my machine isn’t going to be affected by the pad problem. However, while the pads may not be an issue for me, they might be a problem for other people. If you purchase the L4 and decide the pads are inadequate, take a run to your local hardware store because they’ll have suitable replacements. They are extremely inexpensive and will do the job nicely. Nonetheless, Elago definitely needs to rethink the pads on the next revision of the L4. I’m knocking a star off the review as a result of the pad problem.

At this point, I repackaged the stand so I could bring it home.

Using the Elago L4 stand:

One of my first tasks when I got home was to put the L4 into place on my desk. Once again, I took the L4 out of its box and inspected it. The overall workmanship was still impressive. I hadn’t mentioned the color of the L4 previously but I like the silver even if it isn’t a perfect match to my Macbook Pro. To my eyes, the silver color of the stand seems a bit brighter - not shinier - than the silver color of my Macbook Pro. It blends nicely though and the color compliments the steel blue of my Macbook’s Speck case. It blends nicely with the aluminum color of my aluminum USB 3.0 hub. I know the difference in color between the stand and their Macbook may be a problem for some people but it’s a non-issue to me. I wouldn’t let the minor difference in color dissuade me from buying the L4.

I’ve mentioned this before and I’ll say it again. The L4 is a sturdy piece of equipment. I pressed platform and the sides and barely felt any give. However, one question that came to mind is “Will the L4 wobble on my desk when tapped?” I wouldn’t want a wobbly stand for my beautiful Macbook Pro. It’s a little thing that could probably be resolved easily but it would annoy me. I placed the L4 on my desk without anything on it and tapped the side and the top a few times. No wobbles. For what it’s worth, even a very slight wobble would probably have been negated by the weight of the Macbook Pro. It isn’t a heavy computer by any means but the weight is noticeable.

I lifted my Macbook Pro and slid the L4 beneath it and heard what sounded like faint scratching. My assumption about the pads on the runner legs was spot-on. Fortunately, the scratchy sound turned out to be just a scratchy sound. I didn’t see any actual scratches on my desk. This time. My Macbook Pro rested nicely on the L4, though being a 15” model, it hangs over the sides of the stand by about an 1” on each side. This was expected. Elago has a diagram on their web site and on the box of the L4 that demonstrates how laptops of various size will fit on it. 15” and larger laptops like my particular Macbook Pro will hang over the sides. A 13” machine will fit perfectly on the platform!

One of the reasons I chose the L4 was the lip on the front of the stand. This prevents a laptop from slipping off the stand. Many of the L4’s competitors lack a lip and I’d be concerned a laptop sitting on it might slip off onto the desk or, worse, the floor. I use an older version of the Griffin Elevator laptop stand at my office and and it doesn’t have a lip or attachments that served to prevent a laptop from slipping off it, despite the “sticky” padding. Although I’ve not seen a computer slip off the stand, I read enough complaints about it happening that it’s a definite concern. Griffin has since added thiggamajiggies to the front of the elevator.

As with the Rain Design mStand, the lip at the front of the L4 is an actual part of the stand and is definitely tall enough to keep a laptop from slipping off it. My Macbook Pro stays in place nicely. Even bumping my desk wouldn’t make it slip. I gave my desk a bonk just to be sure. There is a caveat, though, and it is one that ought not come as a surprise. The lip makes it difficult to open my Macbook Pro from the front. The RainDesign mStand suffers from the same problem. Again, this is immediately apparent upon viewing a pictures of the L4 and shouldn’t come as a surprise to anyone buying the stand. Fortunately, it’s easy enough to open the Macbook Pro a little by the sides and then open it the rest of the way from the front. This will definitely be an issue for people whose laptops have a latch in the front. If being unable to open the laptop the way you normally would do so, then L4 stand isn’t for you.

Good design can make what seems like a simple product compelling. Unlike the mStand from Rain Design, the L4 isn’t a sideways U shape with a large base and no sides. Rather, it is more like an H with the top portions cut off. Think in terms of a monitor stand. So, the L4 has sides and lacks a back. I preferred this design since I intended to place an MPow 7-port Premium Aluminum USB 3.0 hub beneath the L4. The idea was the open back would allow easy access to the USB ports and power switch of the hub and allows the cables to dangle out the back since most of the items attached to it are on the floor beneath my desk. And, the L4 didn’t let me down. The hub fits nicely beneath the stand and it’s easy to get to its ports and power button. This aspect of the L4 is why I chose it over the mStand. However, while the design works for me, it may not do so for you. The design also creates a caveat which might present a problem.

Unlike the sideways U shape design of the mStand, the base of the “runner legs” of the L4 are only 3/4” wide. This could prove disastrous if the L4 stand is placed too close edge of a surface. Common sense dictates anyone who purchases the L4 would realize this from the day he/she opens the box and place it in an appropriate location. My L4 is on the left side of my desk with the right side of it angled backwards slightly. The stand is far enough from the left edge that it isn’t going to fall off unless someone hits my desk in a manner that results in a truly disastrous bump. If that happens, I’d expect everything to fall onto the floor including the stand, my Macbook, the 27” display and all sorts of other odds and ends. If you choose the L4, please follow my example and take a teensy bit of care when placing the it on your desk.

Once L4 and Macbook Pro were placed exactly how I wanted them on my desk, I had the opportunity to give the stand my second stability test. Typing. Or, should I say, Robert-style machine-gun hunt and pecking. I don’t know how to type but I can hunt and peck really fast. I hunt and peck so fast that people mistake it for typing. My style of hunt and pecking is most assuredly heavy-handed and can sometimes make items sitting on my desk wobble. That includes my 27” display. Although the display is fantastic and comes with a very good base, it’s very wide and susceptible to a little bit of wobble when I hunt and peck at top speed. This doesn’t happen often but I’ve seen it now and again. The macbook pro, on the stand, doesn’t budge. If it wobbles when I hunt and peck, it hasn’t done so enough to be noticeable.

Although I don’t plan to use the L4 stand to raise my Macbook Pro with the intent of using it as a monitor directly in front of me, I decided to assess using it this way for the sake of the review. It works nicely! I slid my Matias Tactile Pro keyboard and Logitech Cordless Optical mouse to their appropriate locations in front of the stand, powered up a word processor on my Macbook and tapped away at full throttle for a few minutes. Admittedly, the high resolution of the retina display of the Macbook Pro made the text on the small side because the laptop was a bit farther away from my eyes than normal but I was still able to treat it as a normal desktop or mini-tower with a display and tap away omn the external keyboard with reasonable confidence. I decided to take this test a step further. Just for giggles, I tried using my Macbook Pro while it was on the stand. No external keyboard or mouse. No external monitor. Just the laptop on the stand in front of me. the experience was far from pleasant. I don’t think the L4 is designed to be used with a laptop in this manner. Sitll, it was worth a try just for the sake of discussion.

Care and maintenance:

That is the question. It’s a laptop stand. You wouldn’t think it requires much care and maintenance. After all, L4 is machined out of solid aluminum. Nonetheless, I would expect it would require dusting and/or wiping with a cloth and such. Unfortunately, Elago doesn’t include in the box or on their web site any care and maintenance instructions at all with the stand. So, it’s up to the owner to determine how to care for it. I’ll probably use a Swiffer duster to wipe it down once in a while. For what it’s worth, I couldn’t find maintenance and care instructions for the Rain Design mStand either.

Some possible improvements for the next revision

As you can imagine, as much as I like the Elago L4 laptop stand, it can definitely use a few modest improvements. The first that comes to mind are the pads used on the legs, behind the anti-slip lip and on the platform itself. This shouldn’t come as a surprise. Thicker pads would be an improvement, especially on the bottoms of the legs. These would ensure the laptop and the surface upon which the L4 is placed is properly protected from scratching. They don’t have to be dramatically thicker but thicker than what’s on the L4 right now. Replacement pads are readily available at any local hardware or big box store. I may purchase them for the legs of the stand. Better pads for the anti-slip lip and the platform are unnecessary since my Macbook Pro is encased in a Speck shell.

I’d also like to see reasonably sized openings in the sides of the L4. This would have little impact on the usability and stability of the stand and make items placed beneath it more accessible. For example… My MPow USB hub is beneath the stand towards the back. There is ample space for a portable hard disk drive in front of it. If there were openings on the sides of the L4 stand, I could slip a portable hard disk drive beneath it, slide a cable through a convenient opening and connect it to my laptop or the USB hub.

Upon my first viewing of the stand on the Amazon web site, I thought the bottom of the legs extended across the entire unit. While the L4 works well as designed, I’d love to see the flat portion of the legs extend from one side to the other. If nothing else, this would reduce the risk of the stand falling off a surfacewhen bumped or pushed. However, I don’t foresee this improvement appearing since the amount of metal and machining necessary to implement it would increase the cost of the stand, possibly considerably. ‘course, it’s easy enough to add a full bottom to the stand as a “Do it yourself” job.

Final assessment:

Don’t hesitate to buy the Elago L4 stand for laptop computers (silver). It’s a very nice stand and will do its job quite well. Is it perfect? No. Mine shipped with missing pads and those that came on it were inadequate. The “runner leg” design of the sides has the potential of being a problem. Fortunately, neither of these issues are enough to detract more than a single star from my rating of the L4 stand. The pad issue is easily resolved and/or can be ignored entirely. A little common sense when placing the stand on a surface makes the other concern a non-issue.

Does the L4 have some nice features? Absolutely. The L4 holds my laptop easily, the lip will prevent it from slipping off the stand and the open design means the space beneath the stand remains useful. Many of the L4’s competitors don’t offer this luxury. Will the L4 do its job? Without a doubt. I’ve used the L4 for several days and I’m very happy with it. I believe it’s going to serve me well for a very long time. Despite the minor flaws, the L4 is a nicely finished, well made, sturdy laptop stand that suits the arrangement of my desktop and my overall my workflow. If you’re in the market for a laptop stand, then you definitely should give the L4 serious consideration.

product_title: Pentel Sharp Kerry Mechanical Pencil, 0.70 mm, Metallic Black Barrel, 1 Unit (P1037A)
review_headline: stuff made today just isn't the good quality of the same items that were made years ...
review_body: I'm sorry, but this is one item whose quality has slipped significantly over the years.  I purchased my first one about 40 years ago.  It worked perfectly for 30 years and would probably still be working perfectly if it hadn't slipped from a not-deep-enough pocket when I was getting into the car.  I didn't realize until I'd gotten home.  I drove back to find it, but it was gone.  All the ones I've bought since have broken in too short a period of time.  I don't know if we can send them back to get them repaired nowadays.  I did send 2 back and Pentel fixed them for free.  But again, they just didn't last as long as my first one (or 2 - I've lost a couple more over the years).  Pentel quit putting the little wire in the eraser for getting out jammed lead.  Bummer.  Those little wires saved the day enough times to make them worth it to me.  I currently have 2 working pencils and 5 that I'm keeping to maybe send back to Pentel because they are broken.  I was able to make one working one from 2 broken ones one time.  As I mentioned in another review, stuff made today just isn't the good quality of the same items that were made years ago.  I think manufacturers are forced to make lesser quality things because John Q. Public refuses to pay for the quality of old.  The quality of old couldn't compete today because it would be too expensive and people wouldn't purchase it.

review_headline: you have to monitor the squeezing - I am right there next to her while she's painting making sure she doesn't squeeze the entire
review_body: My 2.5 year old absolutely loves these glitter paints. Yes, you have to monitor the squeezing - I am right there next to her while she's painting making sure she doesn't squeeze the entire amount out on the paper (which she would love to do lol). They are definitely a "caregiver participation" activity rather than just independent (as opposed to say crayons) - even my 6 year old nephew couldn't resist attempting to squeeze out the entire bottle. That being said, it's well worth the effort to sit and play with these paint pens - the colors are vibrant and the glitter looks great. My daughter asks to play with them all the time. It's much easier to play with these in the summer when we can do it outdoors - indoors, make sure you have a good smock and lots of wet wipes ready!

product_title: HD Chalks Complete Bundle of 52 Unique Chalkboard Labels with Liquid Chalk Marker - Premium Stickers for Jars
review_headline: Wonderful Self-Adhesive Chalk Labels that can be Re-Used!
review_body:
I have some great containers in my pantry, however the only drawback is that it is impossible to tell what is in the canisters! You definitely need to attach some sort of label, but I wanted a label that I could easily change as the contents in the containers changed. Opportunity presented itself when I was asked if I would review these HD Chalkboard Labels that come with a chalk marker. My goodness where have these labels been?! I love them! The labels are self-adhesive and easily peel off the paper they come in. You have to really shake the marker, but then the chalk flows easily for labeling your containers.

I love being able to organize and label anything with these stylish looking labels. They look great on mason jars, canning jars and spice jars. The labels can also be used on cleaners, folders, bottles, office supplies, cleaning supplies, etc. The best part is that theses self-adhesive labels are reusable and waterproof. It's easy to tag the labels and then just wipe it off with a damp cloth. The labels are non-toxic and the marker is made with water based resin liquid chalk.

I labeled my AirScape containers and now I finally know what is inside them! If you like to get a discount for these labels visit my blog
http://www.portraits-by-nc.com/culinary-finds/easiest-way-to-label-airscape-containers-using-chalkboard-labels

product_title: Brother Printer HL2270DW Wireless Monochrome Printer
review_headline: Why do people make things so hard??
review_body:
Great toner, great printer, great support.
I got it before starting my Undergrad, and I graduate coming up in the Fall. I just replaced the cartridge before finals this fall (5 Semesters, and two J-Terms) and being a Physics/CS major I print reports at least biweekly; there were stints where I was printing 3-4 page reflections and 8-10 page formal lab reports a few times a week.

I still had the original cartridge in the thing after almost 3 years of off and on use, it has 995 (791 of which were duplex) pages printed and 34 envelopes, 0 errors, 0 paper jams, it says 99% left on drum, 15% of toner left, 600 DPI, toner save is off. This printer is the perfect printer for me, it is small, fast (enough) if I need a quick 30 pages run off I am going to stop by the lab before class, it doesn't heat up my room, cools off quickly, it is easy to use...what more can I say?!

(^all pulled from the settings printout, see below)

------------------------------------

Things to know... (all pulled from the manual I got with the printer)
*when the printer senses that the cartridge is low (ish) it will halt all printing and flash the toner light:
- press the 'go' button on the top of the machine seven (7) times with all of the doors closed, and it being powered on
- this enables a 'continue' mode when the toner is 'low'
- it can be disabled by pressing the same button seven (7) times again
*to get a printout of settings:
- press the same 'go' button three (3) times

------------------------------------

I really wonder how many one star reviews would not exist if people would just read the darn manual...

having the printer stop printing is not at all a cash grab, it is simply a convince feature so you can have time to order a replacement well before what remains runs out.

product_title: Avery Big Tab Insertable Three-Pocket Corner Lock Plastic Dividers, 5 Multicolor Tabs, 1 Set (11273)
review_headline: Even more pockets in this useful style of (extra-wide) divider
review_body:
Over time, I've decided that dividers such as these, which provide pockets for loose papers, are very useful, and that is what I look for whenever I have to start a notebook for some project or for collecting tax documents, but I can't always find what i want.

These ones are even more useful than ones I have used in the past, because there are two pockets, as well as a full page insertable protector (like for a syllabus or calendar or something). It includes a page of paper tab inserts which you can print on or write on.

The one thing to note is that they are wider than the usual tab dividers, due to the need for the pockets to be wide enough to contain a standard notebook page. Thus, you may want to seek out wider notebooks for use with these tabs. They are almost 9-3/4 inch wide, wider than most notebooks, so that the tabs will be sticking out from standard-width notebooks. Still, these are the most useful dividers I have encountered so far.

product_title: HP 88 Magenta & Cyan Original Printhead (C9382A)
review_body: We were having print quality issues with our 2007 HP All-In-One L7780 and ran the printer diagnostics which indicated the magenta/cyan printhead was bad. It  was the original and lasted for almost 7 years.  So we bought both HP genuine printheads for magenta/cyan and black/yellow through Amazon last July.  After about 6 months, we started having problems with the color printing for the red/orange shades.  We tried new ink cartridges and that didn't work.  The diagnostics indicated both printheads were in a "Yellow" status and needed to be monitored.  The black/yellow we boght last July was just installed today.  I decided to look up the warranty information on HP's site for the two printheads, and it had me enter the serial number and product number for the printheads. To my surprise, HP's site said the printheads expired in Feb 2006.  I still have the original HP packaging which also has the serial number and product number.  It indicated on the box, on the internal package label, and the actual cartridge that the product warranty expired in April 2016.  I will be contacting HP on Monday about this anomaly since the packaging and cartridges appear to be genuine originals.

product_title: Sale !!! H&L Office Mid Back Mesh Executive & Managerial Computer Desk Swivel Office Chair with Headrest and Flexible Arm Rest
review_body:
Well for starters its a chair, not overly comfortable, not overly attractive, just a chair. I bought it for 140 dollars because of some good reviews and I needed a mesh chair opposed to leather, but this chair is worth 100 dollars max, in my oppinion. The head rest is awful, it has a moving part that adjusts it up and down which you cannot tighten with screws, and it wobbles a bit when you lean back on it. It almost feels like it should have been attached at all, but if it wasnt it would hardly be "An executive chair" it would just be a small, medium height chair. It is not a bit chair, or an impressive chair by any means, so if you thought it looked great in the picture, in person it might be a different story.

It IS a chair, so you can sit on it and it and its new so it doesnt wobble... but so is nearly every chair you buy new.

product_title: Protex Through-The-Door Locking Drop Box (WSS-159)
review_body:
We purchased this drop box after having rent checks stolen from our office door mail slot. After installing this drop box, I thought we were safe, but the crooks are smarter than this box. They put a sticky substance on the drawer forks and on the back drop panel and were able to catch checks and fish them out. Three checks were stolen from this box. The police said they get 2-3 reports a day regarding this kind of theft. Don't think your rent checks are safe with this drop box, a thief can still get what they want.
Also, I have called Protex Safe Co. for two days in a row to let them know what happened. They never answer the phone or return calls. Forget about it!

product_title: Iron on Heat Transfer Paper/dark Color 30 Sheets 8.5 X 11 Jet-opaque
review_headline: Don't have your iron too hot
review_body: We used these for a super hero birthday party and ironed them onto red polyester fabric capes that I made for the party favors. They were pretty easy to use and they ironed on well. I'm not planning to wash the capes too much so not sure how well they would do with a bunch of washings. One thing to remember, be sure not to have the iron too hot, or on steam, as it will make steam "holes" on your iron on piece. I lowered the iron temperature closer to a medium setting, turned off the steam, used the parchment paper provided on top of the transfer paper and then added a 100% cotton cloth over the top of the parchment paper before placing the iron on top of it. I didn't move the iron around, I just placed the bigger part of the iron over the top of my transfer piece. It seemed to stick better this way.

product_title: Elmer's Freestyle Repositionable Micro Suction Technology Ruffle Storage Tray, Clear, E6350
review_body:
This is a very useful attachment tray that works on many types of surfaces: Stainless Steel, Finished Wood, Glass, Metal, Plastic, and Tile. It has a clear thin adhesive plastic backing (4in x 6in) with two round holders embedded in a thick oval plastic center. The combination of wide adhesive area and two thicknesses of plastic make this base very good for holding small objects. When you peal off the adhesive backing and place it on a surface, the base is quite strong. It has to set for about an hour to reach maximum holding strength. The tray holds up to 2lbs of objects.

The holding unit bottom surface is 7in x 2in allowing you to put a number of small items in the tray. The tray hooks over the two round holders on the adhesive plastic via holes in the backing of the tray . The two holes have a tear drop shape so the tray can be slid over the holders and seated securely. The tray can be removed by pushing it up and pulling it off of the holders.

If you want to re-position the unit, you can peal off the adhesive and stick it someplace else. The product is made by Elmer's so you can expect good adhesive properties with multiple repositionings. The front and side round edge of the tray has thirteen 1in tall scallops that allow you to hang jewelry chains, key chains, stringed items, etc. The continuous depth of the tray is .25in so paper clips, pins, and other small objects will not fall out.

This is an excellent "Freestyle" tray that I have on the next to my calendars and desk, and I use it every day. It is Made in China.

product_title: HP Officejet Pro 8620 Wireless All-in-One Color Inkjet Printer (A7F65A#B1H)
review_headline: MAJOR Wireless hook-up issue ~ WOULD LOVE SUGGESTIONS!!
review_body: I purchased the HP OfficeJet Pro 8620 two weeks ago, after reading many fine reviews.  I was very excited to get it up and running, so that I get cracking on some school assignments which were due that week.  At the time I bought this printer, I bought a MacBook Pro laptop, and the reason I bought this printer was to be able to print WIRELESSLY, not to mention the other great qualities the printer offered.  I called HP Customer Support to enlist their help in getting the set up accomplished, & I must say, everyone I've spoken to has been extremely professional & nice on the phone.  They were able to remotely connect to my computer (with my consent, of course) and download the program into my Mac, as when I tried, I wasn't sure what I was doing & I didn't want to mess anything up.  Well, the long & short of this is that my printer will not print WIRELESSLY!!!  HP Tech Support said I needed to call my ISP (my router was purchased @ OfficeMax) to have my ISP alter the router settings so that they communicate & my ISP provider said this is HP's issue & they've only ever reconfigured port changes for people who are installing high-end security systems.  So I am at a complete LOSS.  I can print, but I have to go downstairs where the printer & router is and turn the printer OFF, then back ON; the print job with then initiate.  If I don't do this, I get a message on the display screen that the "printer is not connected"; the printer is connected, their is wi-fi connection for sure, but again, the printer won't print until I turn the printer off ~ well, that's pretty frustrating, and HP has been useless (but nice) in helping me to resolve this issue.  I am seriously 5 seconds away from packing it up & sending back!!!

product_title: Brother MFCJ870 Wireless Color Inkjet All-In-One with Scanner, Copier and Fax Printer
review_body:
Been using an HP wireless AIO for several years. Did a decent job of printing both text and graphics, but just didn't like staying on the network. (HP J4680, just in case you're wondering - and I have 3 of them on various networks with similar problems). Plus I've grown to HATE the HP driver suite. So when I was in the market for a new unit, other than NOT being HP, my only requirement was that it could directly print to CD/DVD media. This Brother is a DREAM. Prints at least as well as the HP, seems the ink is cheaper (marginally) and it seems to last better than the HP. Network setup is quick, easy and effective - printer shows up on the network and STAYS on the network. Also, Brother has (free) apps for not only ios and android, but even windows phone 8.1 - you know, the phone OS NOBODY uses (except me...)
Operationally this unit shines (literally) - the control panel is beautifully illuminated, unlike the HP, and the scanning is easily 5x faster, at least. Through in the NFC printing capability (not from my Lumia 920, sorry to say) and a very competitive price, not to mention that CD/DVD capability, and this printer is a winner in my book. Highly recommended, in case you didn't get that from the review <g>

product_title: V-LIGHT LED Energy-Efficient Ultra-Slim Desk Lamp with Adjustable Arms (VSL188NC)
review_body:
The V-Light LED ultra-thin desk lamp is a great desk lamp; in both form and function. Overall, it's a great light for computer work and reading.

-The styling of the lamp is modern and clean, but not to the point it would look out of place on a more traditional desk.
-The lamp base is stable enough, that the LED light source can be positioned far away from the base. That allowed me to hide the base behind my computer monitor.
-There is little to no heat from the lamp.
-The V-shaped light source screen can be rotated to focus the lamps light.
-The light emitted is a bright white closer to sunlight than a typical lamp light.
-Surprisingly, the light leave very little glare on a computer screen.

product_title: 90 Piece Laminating Pouch Sample Pack
review_headline: Very Useful Assortment, Nicely Labeled and Organized
review_body:
I didn't know all the different useful things that could be done with a laminator, but this assortment is a nice way to open up possibilities. It is nice to know that I have all sorts of supplies on hand to use at a moment's notice.

And, the assortment was nicely assembled. Each set of five is in a suitably sized plastic pouch, with a label giving dimensions and thickness, and anticipated use (e.g. "Bookmark - Large"). All of these pouches are in a larger plastic pouch, with a list of the inventory detailed on a cover sheet. The only thing which would have been nicer is if they included loops to go with the luggage tags (so I got some 45lb test self-locking cable ties at my local hardware store instead).

If I let it curve gently, I can store it inside the box with my laminator.

product_title: Ink & Toner Geek ® - 5 Pack Remanufactured Replacement Inkjet Cartridges for Epson T125 #125 (T125120, T125220, T125320, T125420) Black Cyan Magenta Yellow For Use With Epson Stylus NX125 Stylus NX127 Stylus NX130 Stylus NX230 Stylus NX420 Stylus NX530 Stylus NX625, WorkForce 320 WorkForce 323 WorkForce 325 WorkForce 520 (2 Black, 1 Cyan, 1 Magenta, 1 Yellow)
review_headline: at first these cheaper inks seemed like a great idea
review_body:
at first these cheaper inks seemed like a great idea.. until they stopped working. Some wont work at all, some wont work after a few prints. Mainly the black ink it seems. I'm not sure why. It still costs less to buy 100 of these and hope half of them work but it's not worth the unreliability and the headache. I'll have to switch back to epson inks and hope my printer isn't damaged.

update - I replaced them with standard epson inks and after 3 head cleanings, they printer functions properly again. It seem the cheap ink clogs the heads or dries up inside them. It may help to remove the inks between use and replace them with epson carts as a place holder until you need the printer again.

product_title: Sentey GS-2330 Rooted Extreme Gamer Series Mouse Pad, Red & Black
review_body:
The only thought I have after trying this gaming mouse pad by Sentey is why did I wait so long to throw away my small one with the gel pad wrist support??? This is unimaginably better in every way to that! The old mouse pad didn't leave much room to move the mouse without running off the mouse pad. Totally constricting and uncomfortable!

On the other hand, this Rooted gaming mouse pad is large enough that I have plenty of room to move around without the mouse ever going off the pad, and the rubber backing clings to my desk and doesn't slip or slide when the mouse is moved around on it. The surface is satiny smooth and my laser mouse glides around it quickly without any sticking issues or losing contact.

The mouse pad comes in a gorgeous gift worthy box, so it's rolled up, but it flattened out except for some curl at the far right edges when I first laid it out and I'm sure that will flatten out a I use the pad more. It seems very well made to me - the design is stunning, the fabric on the top is so satiny smooth, the edges are neatly reinforced and machine stitched so the binding is very solid, and it appears it will be very durable, and most important to me at least, it's just the right thickness to be extremely comfortable to use.

I could kick myself for taking so long before replacing the old mouse pad with this one, but now that I've seen the quality of this pad I'll be back to replace our other mouse pads as well. Disclaimer: I received a discount on this product for purposes of my evaluation - no obligations. My review is entirely based on my personal examination of the mouse pad and using the mouse pad itself in order to determine it's quality and functionality. In my opinion, this product deserves five well earned stars.

product_title: Epson WorkForce WF-7110 Wireless and WiFi Direct, Wide-Format Color Inkjet Printer, 2-Sided Auto Duplex. Prints from Tablet/Smartphone. AirPrint Compatible. (C11CC99201)
review_headline: Setup was super simple unlike my last printer I got 6 years ...
review_body:
So far this thing is a dream. Had it a couple weeks now. I'll try to remember to update as time goes on.

Setup was super simple unlike my last printer I got 6 years ago. We're using this WF-7110 wireless for all 4 desktops in the house and setup was super duper simple. Again unlike my last printer that was wireless we could never get it working but this one one works on both our Win 7 and Win 8.1 machines.

Prints are AMAZING! I added two photos that I printed out and scanned. They look even better in person but you can tell here how high quality the prints are. What really amazed me specifically was the dithering of colors where they blend or something is supposed to be translucent over-top another color... prints perfectly smooth.

I was on the fence between this WF-7110 and the Artisan 1430. If you go to the Epson website and look at the detailed specs between the two... nearly identical. Without having both and doing test prints I'm not sure how you could tell the difference. My best *guess* is that since the Artisan 1430 has more color cartridges that you *might* get superior color quality and color matching. They also use slightly different ink types. Best I could find for differences in other peoples reviews were that the 1430 was better for actual photo printing. The 7110 will do photo printing but there was a complaint that the dye based ink in the 7110 dries very slowly on the glossy photo paper and you have to be super careful not to touch the print for a day. Well our use case was not for photo prints. We do lots of card-stock crafts like models, party invites, decorations, etc. etc. Also print out lots of lists, short term calendars, kids homework projects, and such.

Another aspect of the print quality that found astonishing was how sharp the text is. It's truly as good as any laser I've ever seen. That's usually where the laser printers are superior; sharp lines, edges, corners... Epson wasn't kidding when they said it beats leaser printers.

As with my previous printer I went ahead and bought ink cartridges that you refill yourself. There's an inksupply company you can find that sells kits. Simply look up the make and model. This drives the price-per-print so low that you're more concerned with the price of paper than ink!

I jut hope we can get another 6 years out of this printer.t kidding when they said it beats leaser printers.

product_title: Canon PIXMA MG6220 Wireless Inkjet Photo All-in-One Printer (5292B002)
review_headline: Bottom line, hardware/printing is good, software/firmware/drivers could be improved a lot.
review_body: Prints well, but as other mentioned, it does say ink is out quickly!  I have discovered though that if I leave the ink tanks in and continue using them after getting the "ink is out" message, that it just keeps printing.  I use it only periodically, but I easily go another 3 months on a tank after it says it was empty- I run it with the "empty" tank until the printing comes out poorly.  I never change it at the moment it says to change it.  That said, I hate the software it installs on my pc and that seems necessary to be able to use any functions besides basic printing... like being able to scan.  This software requires desktop space and gets in the way of other items on my computer's desktop.  It's difficult to use.  And the drivers seem to have some issues.  I set it up for wireless printing and sometimes the printer and my devices have trouble communicating with each other.  For basic printing and copying it's great so long as you ignore the messages to change your ink.  For sending scans to your computer wirelessly... it sometimes works great and sometimes has major issues.  So bottom line, hardware is good, software/firmware/drivers could be improved a lot.

review_body:
Very useful and sturdy clipboard. Probably my favorite part about this clipboard is the "clipping" mechanism on this product. Instead of the "counter-traction downwards force" you use to secure papers on traditional clipboards - you simply lift the clip and secure papers to this board instead.

The material that this clipboard is made out of is also very nice. It's smooth and matte, and nice to touch.

product_title: Avery Durable Write-On Plastic Dividers with Expandable Pockets, 5-Tabs, 1 Set (16183)
review_headline: Great for organizing a larger binder and loose papers
review_body: As a college student taking up to four classes at a time, plus volunteering, scholarship applications, study abroad materials, and a lot of other stuff to manage, a big binder with divided sections has become a daily companion. I primarily use a Halodex, but because of the size of the covers, the divider tabs get ratty after a few terms, so I replace them occasionally. These are the most durable I've found so far, and the pockets are a NECESSITY for holding weekly projects, syllabi, applications, reference works, and so on. The colors make for quick location of the desired subject. The Avery binder is really nice because it's sized to protect the tabs from protruding, which makes it slightly wider than the Halodex. I prefer the Halodex because of the ability to fold it over on itself and still ay totally flat, and these work just fine in it other than the protruding tabs.

product_title: Panasonic Link2Cell Bluetooth Enabled Phone KX-TG7875S
review_body: Works directly to 220v!! (yes! even if the adapters say 110v only). I know it because I tested them myself and I've been using them that way for a week already. Before doing it I found a chinese website from a guy that tested them directly to 220v and was working. I needed to translate the website (google) but wasn't fully clear if all worked or only the base station, so I connected all the adapters and checked the output voltage with a tester (with and without a 220v-110v transformer). Same voltage so I connected everything and worked.  The base station and handsets are awesome. Only downside is that you have to keep the manual since some initial programming is made by entering 3 or 4 digit codes (weird). For example the Bluetooth pairing is done that way, and there are no menu options for that.  Something excellent is that you can transfer all the phone numbers from the cell phones to the a shared contact list (shared between all the handsets and the base station). Another feature that I liked is that even if someone is talking on the phone (with one of the handsets) you can take another handset and call a thirds handset, and talk at the same time. I still have to test if this also works when you are using one of the handsets for a cell phone communication.  Highly recommended really!

product_title: Epson Perfection V39 photo Scanner
review_body:
The great thing about this scanner is its kickstand. When I first went about scanning with my other scanner it would end up being precariously tilted on my printer, making for some awkward reaches. This one takes up much less desk space.

I don't have a convenient CD drive, so I found the Mac driver on Epson's site. Installation was easy after that. Even though I had this plugged into a USB 3 port, I would not call this speedy, it's not horrible but would be frustrating if I were in a hurry.

My other Epson scanner—the Perfection 370—has a negative/slide option albeit a clumsy one. So those needing to scan negatives, could try that instead.

Image quality is fairly good. Some of my old prints turned out great. Others not so much. In particular, it seemed like the "backlight correction" always made the image worse, so turn it off.

I'm just happy to have finally scanned my photos from 1988.

product_title: HP Officejet Pro 8620 Wireless All-in-One Color Inkjet Printer (A7F65A#B1H)
review_headline: Print quality is lousy.  Don't buy if you plan to print photos and want them to be of decent quality.
review_body: 1 Star?  Good I got your attention.  Now listen or read carefully.  This is truly a small office printer.  If you want this for your home office and expect it to work for both your small business and for home uses such as printing pictures and photos don't buy it.  The photo quality with this unit is terrible.  The pictures are dark and to overcome that you have to use the HP editing software and bump up the exposure.  HP Automatic adjustments don't get the job done.  I replaced my Kodak all-in-one with this and while it outperforms the Kodak in office functions(it should its is 5 years newer and $150 more) it absolutely sucks when printing photos. And I had both printers working side by side on the same photo.  No comparison.  The Kodak print quality was better on everything.  On documents but especially on photos.  I can tolerate average quality text in documents.  So what, as long as its readable. But when I print photos I want them to be good. Too bad, I could like a lot about this printer.  But at my house I didn't want two printers, two sets of ink cartridges, and so on.  But if I keep this I will need a dedicated photo printer.

review_headline: QUALITY NOT QUITE WHAT IT USED TO BE...
review_body:
This is my second unit of this version from Fellowes.
My first unit developed a defective on/off power switch after 5 years; but aside from that worked flawlessly.

In addition, my old unit came with a paper tray which mounts via slots on the side of the unit.
This unit was missing the paper tray. I do not know if this was accidentally not included or if this vendor is dispensing with including the paper tray in an effort to reduce costs.

In addition, the power cord on this unit is far less heavy duty than that of my old unit. Moreover, It cannot be removed. The power cord on this unit is hard wired into the motor.

All in all though, the unit is still a good value for the job it does. I was just a bit disappointed. I kind of wish I'd kept my old model and cabbaged parts to upgrade this one.

Excellent service from the vendor though. The unit arrived about four days ahead of schedule.

CONS: my camera arrived with the default on-screen language set as Chinese and after many hours of utter frustration and fruitless attempts to switch to English I have tossed the camera out. The manual says that you can switch languages from the on-screen 'settings' position but if all the language on-screen is in Chinese, you can't even find the 'settings' option. I have been unable to switch from Chinese to English on my camera. All attempts to reach the manufacturer, distributor or customer service for help have gone unanswered.

CONCLUSION: I do not recommend this camera unless you are fluent in Chinese.

product_title: LAMY Safari Fountain Pen Charcoal Ex-Fine (L17EF)
review_headline: A decent pen that I hoped would have been better
review_body:
I have always been into fountain pens and never really knew which one to buy. I have seen some very expensive pens (those are way too much for me) and some very inexpensive pens (the reviews weren't that good). While looking around on Amazon I stumbled upon this pen. I read the others reviews and they seemed decent even if the price was more than I wanted to spend on a pen at the time. Admittedly, the price isn't that expensive compared to other pens on the market.
Once I received the pen I was pretty excited to open the box and see what I had purchased. The pen looked nice, it is a pretty good construction and it's pretty light, although I did think it was going to be a little heavier. The cartridge was pretty easy to install and the ink flowed pretty good while writing with it. I was a little worried that it would leak while in my pocket, but I have never had an issue with that happening.
After carrying this pen around for a few months I was a little disappointed that the finish on the pen clip started to chip away revealing the copper color underneath. I would have liked to think that this wouldn't have happened, but it did. I also noticed that after writing with this pen that it was a little scratchy compared to other fountain pens that I have purchased since owning this pen. I haven't used it as much and have since started to use another pen that wasn't so scratchy. Since I didn't know better I didn't think it was that big of a deal or that it was normal, but after using other pens I realized how this is a minor annoyance and it can scratch the paper you are writing on. Overall, I liked the pen, but I probably won't buy another one of these pens.

product_title: Sennheiser OfficeRunner Convertible Wireless Office Headset with Microphone - DECT 6.0
review_body: Recently a colleague was complaining how he had to hold the phone for half an hour or however long it takes to screen a potential interview candidate. For times like those OfficeRunner is a great helper, where you dont have to hold the chunky receiver against your ear, and struggle with the other hand to take notes. I must admit that I was overwhelmed by the options behind the base. Then I contacted the headsets company. very promptly, they pointed me to the support page. In the dot com age I should have thought of going to the website instead of being stuck on wanting a paper manual. The videos on the support page are very helpful in terms of the setup, should you want to use the phone option. I used the pc option and conducted a call from skype to skype. The ear loop head set is weightless and pressure free as you dont have to put in into your ear and worry about when its gonna fall off. You have to answer the call by accepting the call on the skype. For interview purposes, since it is a set time and you are the one beginning to call, this is not an issue. The sound quality is very good. The roaming range too is long. When I see people in the doctors's office, multi tasking with a headset on, they feel like super people. Hope you exude that when you have this on and are not stuck to your desk. Review based on complimentary product.

product_title: Mount-it! Monitor Wall Mount with Dual Spring Arm
review_body: I bought 3 of these to mount 3 Asus VG248QE monitors.  They work very well with only having the adjust the springs a little bit.  I had no issues with the plastic wire clips on them and was able to route fairly thick DVI cables and the power cable through them with ease.  The only thing I was a bit disappointed in were the anchors that came with them that were supposed to be used for concrete anchoring according to the manuals.  They seemed very flimsy but the bolts that came with for stud mounting were substantial.  Approximately 2 1/2" long 1/4" lag bolts that hold everything very securely.  All three monitors are up on the wall with very little effort.  Everything went together easily and the instructions were easy to follow.  Everything feels nice and sturdy and the monitors move around easily but stay where you put them with little effort.  I would have liked if there was a version of these that had both arms hinged to allow for greater movement but those are prohibitively expensive.  For the price these work just as well as the name brand counterparts they are modeled after.

review_headline: Now everybody fights over cleaning the windows! :)

Now everybody wants to clean the windows!

This is great! It's very light and compact, and you literally just pop the squeegy head on, and you're away.

I've used it on my windows - its brilliant and leaves no streaks. I also tried it on my bathroom tiles. and found it was much better to use ths than dry all the tiles by hand.

My son works for a major electrical retailer, and I was stunned to find that this is one of their best selling lines! Would you believe it?!

I wouldn't class this as a must have, because we can all do without it, but it definitely does make cleaning a little quicker.

product_title: AGPtEK Call Center Dialpad Corded Headset Telephone
review_headline: Do you have difficulty hearing sometimes? Consider that this has no volume control
review_body: I was soooo excited about this headset/phone that I needed to work efficiently from my desk, keeping my hands free. The price is quite less than others and I like the phone base! It is great! It is the headset that I am unhappy with, and even worse, the type of connection that it has to plug in to the base of the phone, is an uncommon connector to try to replace the headset part with another one. It is not a 3mm or USB or standard connection, so I have to replace the entire thing. Unfortunately I cannot return it, because I initially thought it was great and began using it. When you answer calls for a living you have to be able to hear the client on the other end, and this does not allow me to accomplish this with about 25% of my calls! Which affects my level of service provided. If there were a volume slide, or perhaps even a double ear piece it wouldn't be so bad, but I  struggle  quite a bit with some calls and that is touch! I wish I had paid better attention to the connector in case I needed to replace the head set for some reason down the road. My clients can hear me and the head set is comfortable! So those are positive parts of the review. Unfortunately, trying to save money and try this company's unit, will end up costing me much more in the long run.

product_title: BAM POS, Thermal Receipt Paper 2 1/4" x 85' Paper Tray Pack (10 Rolls)
review_headline: Perfectly adequate paper at a great price
review_body:
We use this thermal receipt paper at my place of business exclusively for credit card receipts. The paper seems a bit thinner and rougher than some other higher-priced brands, but I've never had any problem with the paper jamming in the machine nor tearing inappropriately. The words are easy to read -- there is a fair contrast between dark and white -- and our logo image comes out decently. The thermal printing does not fade away too quickly, either.

My only complaint is that my customers simply can't sign this paper using a regular ballpoint pen on our store's counter. We need something between the receipt paper and the counter (a pad of regular notebook paper works fine) in order for ink to appear. This is obviously an easy fix. And this thermal paper was available at an excellent price, so it's well worth the minor headache.

This may seem obvious, but I should add a caveat that you'll have to be careful to buy the right size thermal paper. The differences in size seem very small, but at least with my machine, you simply can't substitute a 1 3/4" roll in place of a 2 1/4" one.

It leaves a mark on white paper that is almost as dark as a number 2 pencil.  If you're expecting ink, you'll be disappointed.  If you want a pencil that doesn't need sharpening this may be for you.  If you lay down a thick enough area, it can, indeed, be smeared with a fingertip.  Thin lines are difficult to smear but if you go over an area several times, it's smear-able.  This is not a bad thing for drawings, but if you emphasize things by going over them more than once, don't count on them not smearing.

product_title: DBPOWER Video Projector 854*540 2000 Lumens HD Home Theater Multimedia LCD Projector HDMI USB TV DVD WII
review_body:
[[VIDEOID:e1e66635f5027523a8437b30573fb316]] What a nice projector. It's huge, with the biggest lens I've ever seen. It comes with a remote control, lens paper, an extra fuse, a VGA cable, an RCA cable, and even a coaxial cable connector male/female converter. No HDMI cable was included, but there's an HDMI port. I skipped the cables and used my flash drive. The projector has two USB ports for those who need them.

Controls are located on the top, but it's very basic. I prefer using the remote. The only problem is the IR receiver sits on the front of the projector, the same as on other projectors I've owned. I always sit behind the projector. That's about the only thing I don't care for.

I started watching right away on my cloth backdrop that doubles as my screen. One thing I that had my heart off the bat is the keystone correction, which we use to adjust the image when we project it up or downwards at an angle to our screen. That way, our image always looks rectangular, not like a trapezoid. The volume is adjustable and can be quite loud. And how are the videos? During daylight hours with the shutters closed, I can see the image but not that well. At night, with the room lights on, it's perfectly doable. Watch in the dark, and it shines.

product_title: 32GB Strontium NITRO 466X Microsdhc UHS-1 memory Card with Idrive Card Reader
review_body: I realize that 'technically' a TI-83 is just as good. I bought a used TI-83 off Amazon for a my Statistics class and while the 83 was good, there were some variations that made things a bit difficult. Math is not my strong point, so when following directions on how to enter problems, I needed exactly what the instructions used -- and that was a TI-84. I was getting SO frustrated with my TI-83 and was getting nervous as my first exam is next week. I bought this calculator new and also ordered a cute Guerilla cover bundled from Amazon (the seller) using Prime and I actually got it the next DAY. (Props to Amazon and their shipping!) I have SUCH a sense of relief that I am now armed with what I need for Stats and my upcoming Chemistry classes. If you're debating on whether to get the TI-83 vs. the TI-84, do yourself a favor and just get the 84. It will save you some confusion if you are mildly math challenged, like myself. I wish I had done more research and gone with the 84 in the first place.

Pros

product_title: TaoTronics Handheld Mobile Document Portable Scanner 900DPI Color & Mono (For Business, Photo, Picture, Receipts, Books, JPG / PDF Format Selection, Micro SD Card required but not included)
review_headline: I had tried a few different models of the Pandigital wand scanners and they were pretty good but I had heard that this one produ
review_body:
I collect and restore arcade machines and I wanted to buy a wand scanner to scan in the artwork so that I could clean it up digitally and have new artwork printed. I had tried a few different models of the Pandigital wand scanners and they were pretty good but I had heard that this one produced better quality scans... it doesn't.

The color reproduction on this scanner is a tad better than the Pandigital but the roller mechanism design on the Pandigital is superior by a long shot. This uses a single roller and the rubber isn't very grippy meaning that when you're scanning it has a tendency to twist and screw up your scan, if you're super careful it will come out wavy at best... and at worst it will look like it came out of a broken fun-house mirror. this is based on me scanning large smooth and hard surfaces i can't imaging trying to get a good scan out of a magazine or a piece of paper that is more likely to shift around on you. Honestly if you're just trying to take quick pictures of documents or pictures you'd be better just taking a picture with your cell phone.

If you need a properly scanned item then the Pandigtial scanners are much MUCH better for this task. they use a double roller design with a mechanism to make sure that all of the rollers turn at the same rate as a result, as long as what you're scanning is flat it wont ever shift around on you and you get good straight scans as long as you've got a steady hand.

product_title: OBi200 1-Port VoIP Phone Adapter with Google Voice and Fax Support for Home and SOHO Phone Service
review_body:
I've been using Ooma Telo VOIO devices for my home and business phones for several years. I've been highly satisfied with Ooma, which offers great sound quality, rich features, and excellent ease of use. However, Ooma is also moderately expensive (over 100 dollars) and involves ongoing monthly charges (less than 5 bucks for basic service). Recently, I needed to add another dedicated VOIP line. This line didn't need all the Ooma features, so I decided to try a bare bones solution. I found this OBi200 based on all the positive Amazon reviews. I set it up last month and have been really happy with it. This is a great way to get a "landline" at minimal cost. Here's a quick summary of key points:

- The sound quality is as good as my Ooma Telo units, and dramatically better than MagicJack, etc.
- Unlike Ooma, the OBi200 does not come with a VOIP service. You need to register it with the VOIP service of your choice. I'm using it with a Google Voice number. The advantages are that Google Voice is free (no monthly charges) and I really like Google Voice's features (ringing multiple lines, sending text transcriptions of voicemail messages, etc.). The disadvantage is that you have to set up and link a Google Voice number -- not at all difficult, but a little more work than just activating an Ooma.
- Relative to PC-based solutions (Skype, Google Hangouts, etc.), this is a super convenient solution. If you plug a multi-handset phone system into the OBi, it's just like having an old-fashioned land line system, with phones in every room, except that the quality is better and there are no monthly charges.

I'm still using my Ooma devices for my business lines. Ooma is still my preferred solution for creating VOIP that feels just like a telco landline once it's set up. But if you're looking for a cheap, high-quality VOIP solution to give you a "landline" without the cost, and if you already have a Google Voice number or don't mind setting one up, this is an absolutely awesome device. Based on my own use, I highly recommend both Ooma and OBi; if you're a bit of a techie, use Google Voice, and are looking to keep costs to a minimum, this OBi is the way to go.on't mind setting one up, this is an absolutely awesome device. Based on my own use, I highly recommend both Ooma and OBi; if you're a bit of a techie, use Google Voice, and are looking to keep costs to a minimum, this OBi is the way to go.

product_title: Daler-Rowney Simply Portable Field Easel
review_headline: Bought this as backup easel for full time caricature work.
review_body: I am a full time caricature artist and was looking to replace my wooden french easel which was  bulky, heavy and a real pain to set up. My wooden easel has a complex screw tightening sytem that kept coming undone while I worked. A fellow caricature artist was using the compact metal tripod type and recommended it to me. Bought this  model at Walmart for around $20.  So I guess it is fine for the price I paid.  Bought it as a backup in case my other metal tripod easel I ordered from Amazon fails me on a contract caricature gig. That would be a real issue I could not afford.  I recommend having backup easels for anyone doing contract gigs, and production level work. No matter what brand of this style you get, the plastic clips for the leg extensions can break. So I am being very carefull with mine so I dont get stuck. All in all, this easel may work fine for someone doing small or light work if you are careful with the clips.  But my drawing board is 24" tall and this easel is not designed well for something this big or bigger.  The central beam will fit into a square holder for stablity, which it cannot do on larger canvases. That makes the central beam which your drawing board rests on flimsy and unstable.  It bends a little when you apply any amount of pressure.  Also it takes a little finagling to get central beam into the slot for smaller work while still fitting the holder tray onto the two screws on both sides at once.  So I gave this 3 stars instead of 2 since it is a lower priced easel.

There are two things I would change with this. It has one handle which does a person no good if he or she wants to carry it using the handle. I would add a second handle. product_title: T-3000 Tenergy USB Emergency In/Out Charger for Mobile Phones, MP3, Portable Games Devices
review_body:
I got this as a free addon with a Tenergy battery charger purchase about 7 years ago and it's been in my briefcase since. It's great to charge my travel mouse and toothbrush batteries when needed, and in a pinch to get a little juice from them into my phone. Other reviewers said they had trouble getting AA batteries to fit. There is a catch opening it at the AAA size, but it opens all the way with a little more effort. One reviewer had trouble using it to charge his phone. I've used it with various iPhones and I just checked it with an iPhone 5, 6, and iPad 4. Worked exactly as designed.

I don't disagree with reviewer who said a micro USB cable would be ideal, and I do carry a little micro USB for charging my headphones, so I guess it would be nice to have one less cable knocking around my briefcase, but it's never been a huge deal. This thing stays packed away until I need it, which is really only a few times a year if I do a good job of swapping batteries out when I'm home.

product_title: E-Z Ink (TM) Compatible Toner TN660 TN630 High Yield Cartridge Replacement for Brother (1 Black) Compatible With HL-L2320D HL-L2380DW HL-L2340DW MFC-L2700DW MFC-L2720DW MFC-L2740DW MFC-L2707DW Printer
review_headline: Not so fast... read the whole review
review_body:
I have purchased many Genuine Brother cartridges for my office printers over the years. I was always skeptical of the generic brands but after reading the reviews on this toner I took a chance. I cannot tell the difference in quality and I highly recommend this product. I will keep buying EZink brand as long as the quality doesn't slip.

UPDATE: Ironically, the day after I post the 5 star review, the toner is getting weak & gray down the middle of the page. In the past, my Brother printer warns me that the toner is low about 2 weeks before it quits. No "low toner" message yet so we will see if it quits without notice or just gets grayer. Stand by for final update...

FINAL UPDATE: The day after the gray streaks began, the print quality is too poor to continue using and the "Low toner" message came up from my printer. I removed the toner and shook it but no improvement. I don't count pages but I have been buying Genuine Brother toner every 60-75 days and this toner lasted 40 days. I took a chance and ordered a replacement EZink (same product) but that's not what was delivered. The package does not match the picture on the website and the box looks more generic (see attached). I'm all for saving money but it's disappointing when the product fails prematurely and the seller doesn't ship what they advertise. I have lost all confidence and I will go back to buying Genuine Brother. Bummer that the price is so much higher but at least I can count on the quality and the product I receive will match the pic.

product_title: Shell-D RFID Blocking Credit Card Protector - Save Thousands in losses and Headaches
review_body:
This is the third one of these that I have purchased. Basically put, we live now in a cashless society, and the cards I need are less than 10, so this has become my wallet. After going through 4 sets of credit cards, I decided to raise my wall of security and so far (4 months), I have not had a weird purchase put on my credit card. I find that the smooth surface and rounded shape is really easy to slip in and out of pockets. The case is comfy in the hand, easy to manipulate in the palm for opening and closing.
It has been such a hit in my office that most of my co-workers have bought them, remarking how much lighter their pockets seem with these.
The only warning for use is to not overstuff them, as the hinges will burst, but that is fairly obvious.
With a low entry point for trial, I suggest that everyone could use one of these cases, they simply do exactly what they are intended to do, carry your cards, and protect your identity and credit cards from theft. I love them. I am buying more for secondary sets of cards like health care, metro, business cards and lesser used cards.

product_title: BCH Premium Ink Refill Kit for HP 10 11 88 940 XL Color Cartridges H1010C
review_body: I followed the instructions with every detail, and when completed I turned the cartridge over to have ink leak EVERYWHERE!!!!! I'm guessing that within my 940 regular and 940 XL cartridges, there's a "foil bag" of sorts to hold the ink. Well, it seems that in the "injection" or "removing air" portion of the process with a syringe and hypodermic needle, the "bag" has gotten punctured. When this leaks everywhere, it gets on your hands, clothes, furniture, desk, carpeting, dog and any garbage can that you ran to in order to dispose of this ink bomb immediately. I had the same issue with the black XL cartridge, and 2 out of the 3 color cartridges. Horse dung. Process needs to be fixed a bit to prevent this from happening. Use shorter needles perhaps. Now, not only am I out the refills, but I have to go buy new OEM cartridges, because mine are shot. I wish it worked because $15.00 for both the black and color cartridges refilled is a heck of a lot cheaper than $100.00 to replace them.

product_title: OBi100 VoIP Telephone Adapter and Voice Service Bridge
review_body: I signed up for voice-over-IP service a month ago (with voip.ms).  I plugged this in to my wired router, got some settings straight between the Obi config web page and voip.ms and quickly had a dial tone.  It's been running for about a month with no problems.  I have it plugged into a print/scanner/fax machine and then the output of that plugged into a 5 handset cordless phone.  I cannot tell any loss of voice quality compared with a landline.  (Internet service is 30Mbps cable modem.)  I have not done much faxing with it.  I tried to send one fax and it was successful, but I do not know how reliable that will turn out to be since it does not specifically claim fax capabilities.  I don't fax that often, so I guess I'll eventually find out if that works.  (For what I am saving to drop Verizon and go to voip.ms, it will be worth it if it takes a couple of attempts to send a fax.)  As long as it doesn't stop working suddenly, I can't think of any complaints.  (The box itself is around the size of a deck of cards.)  (You do need at least some tech savvy to get this all set up and working, but you probably wouldn't be looking at this if you didn't.  If you've set up a wireless router before and some vague notion of VOIP concepts, it should be easy for you.  If not, then something a little less DIY might be for you. )

product_title: Beam System for Remote Communications Plus Dock
review_headline: Excellent way to attend meetings remotely
review_body:
I have been using a Beam+ at work for the past year or so and I'm very happy with it. At the simplest level, you can think of it as "Skype on Wheels," but that combination is surprisingly effective. You get to attend meetings alongside the people seated around the table, with the ability to turn and look at the screen or the speaker. You just show up, like anyone else attending the meeting, complete with hallway chats before and after. The experience is considerably more engaging than conventional video/teleconference alternatives.

There are a few areas that could benefit from improvement. One is that the image quality isn't great compared to, for example, a Dropcam. It's certainly good enough, though, since the quality of the audio (mic and speakers) is excellent. Another drawback is that the maximum speed is pretty pokey. Finally, it would be nice to have longer battery life.
