product_title: Canon PIXMA iP4200 Photo Printer
review_headline: Another great entry to the PIXMA line of printers
review_body: I usually don't write reviews on products like these unless I have had a negative experience, time to change that.  I had to write a review on this to let anyone who is looking for a printer that this in the one.  I've been using the iP4200 for about a year and a half now and in that time I have had no troubles at all.  I print many full page color photographs, and even with all my printing it still took me about a year until I needed to replace an ink cartridge.  With a regular printer it would have been giving me a low ink warning after just a couple of prints.  Not to mention the price of ink for the Pixma printers.  Not only does it seem to last a long time, but if you don't mind non-oem cartridges the ink is incredibly cheap! We're talking about $1 a piece per cartridge.  My two primary printers are the iP4200 and a Pixma MP620 all-in-one and they have both been amazing.  You can still find these new in box for around $150 and I say it is well worth the price.  Personally I picked mine up for $3.99 at a thrift store! Amazing printer at $3.99 or $200!

product_title: CPR V202 Call Blocker - Block All Robocalls, Political Calls, Scam Calls, Telemarketing Calls, Unwanted Calls On Landline Phones. Block All Nuisance Calls At The Touch Of A Button Using Caller Id
review_body: I got this a week ago and I couldn't be more satisfied. it was easy to hook up and easy to input telephone numbers in to block all those unwanted calls that I've been getting for the last 2 years.  I have only had one unwanted call and that was from a company that used another number to try to trick me. guess what? That number is now blocked too!  I have twenty five specific numbers blocked as well as unavailable and blocked numbers. this thing really works and I recommendi that if you're having trouble with unwanted calls the CPR call blocker is a great solution. wish I'd known about it 2 years ago.

I got them today and when I opened my package the box the highlighters came in was completed busted opened from both ends. That's not a huge deal but when I tried the highlighters I was disappointed. They are very wet, the wettest Ive ever used and when you lift the highlighter from the page the ink pools in that spot and leaves a dark mark. (See photo) Also, you have to hold the highlighter perfectly to get a full line with no patches. (As can be seen in the photo, especially with the blue.)That's a problem I've never really had before and I'm pretty sure it's because the nib of the highlighter is very hard, not cushy at all. It's like a rock. I am disappointed in these highlighters overall, though the colouring of them is perfect and exactly what I wanted. They aren't super neon, just nice.

product_title: EPS compatible replacement for Samsung MLT-D103L - High Yield (ML-2955ND/DW, SCX-4729FD/FW)
review_body: The product works well and I had no difficulties in installing it. The EPS reported page yield is based on 5% coverage of a sheet of paper, which is much less than a fully printed manuscript sheet. If you print manuscripts and full page reports as I do, or if you print graphics, the toner cartridge will run out much sooner than you might expect. If you expect to get 2,000 sheets for example, your actual yield might be only 500 sheets. I wish manufacturers would use realistic percentages for page coverage based on a full page of single or even double-spaced text, but consumers are stuck with the 5% coverage estimate. From what I can tell, all cartridge companies do this for their benefit to inflate their product; such a poor estimate does not in any way benefit the consumer.

product_title: Epson Expression Premium XP-820 Wireless Color Photo Printer with Scanner, Copier and Fax
review_headline: Endless source of frustration. I am sorry I bought it.
review_body: Having had this printer for a few months now, I am surprised how much frustration and time it cost me - and besides I am not happy with the paper handling and some other design features. I am using Mac OS from three computers. The wireless connection keeps failing, and the printer cannot be found after one print job, until you turn it on and off. I reset it several times. After a software (firmware, I think) update, it seemed to finally work, but then starting acting up again. At some point I got a "filer error"... Another internet search, resets, workarounds... Printers should not be so complicated. Just tried the Epson website again, and received "We're sorry, but the Epson America website is currently undergoing maintenance to better serve your needs." Tried connecting via Ethernet cable, no good. Tried via USB to the router - and only succeeded after a couple of help articles online. I am otherwise a VERY savvy tech user, this experience stands out compared to all other experiences i had with technology in recent years. I never need manuals. It reminds me of the bad old days of the 90s (and when I briefly tried Vista...). I cannot believe the reviews and Consumer Reports were so misleading.

product_title: Five Star Expanding File, 6-Pocket, 13 x 9-3/8 Inches, Blue/Yellow/Green Striped (73078)
review_headline: Not a True Expansion File; Slick Surface Makes It Hard to Carry
review_body:
Made of thin plastic, this FIVE STAR EXPANDING FILE is durable, but it's so smooth and slick, it's awkward to pick up or carry around with other books and papers. I think that the standard accordion file made of heavyweight brown paper that ties with a soft string is much easier to use. This plastic file has an excellent closure comprised of strong elastic that fits around a button--but the slick file surface makes closing the file into a two-handed job. Because of the flap at the top, the file isn't suitable for use in a file cabinet drawer, either.

The file is 1\\" thick at the bottom, and this is the actual paper-holding capacity. At the top, the interior section dividers fan out to a width of 6-1/2\\", but this only makes it easier to view the papers inside. The file does not expand to hold more papers, the way that an accordion-style file does.

The blue, yellow, green, gray, and white design looks exactly like the product photo--rather garish and ugly. Because the file doesn't expand to increase capacity and is too slick to carry around easily, I rate it at 2 stars (\\"I don't like it\\" on the official Amazon scale).

product_title: Rechargeable replacement Bt-446 Battery for Uniden cordless phone DC 3.6V 800 mAh
review_headline: Significantly smaller and lighter than original Uniden BT-446. Not a proper replacement. Can it really be an 800mAh NiMH?
review_body:
My original Uniden BT-446 batteries were each 5cm long and weighed 41 grams. These knock-off BT-446's were about 4.5cm long and weighed 32 grams. Yet they claimed to be 800mAh NiMH batteries just like the original. I don't think there's been a revolution in NiMH battery design in the last 8 years that would allow a ~25% weight and significant volume savings while still providing the same 800mAh. No wonder people are saying they don't get the same talk time with these that they got with the original genuine Uniden batteries.

The length difference also means they don't fit as snugly in the battery compartment, so they could rattle around. Also, the electrical leads were longer on these knock-offs, making it harder to get the battery cover on.

They were just $2 each, but I think I'm going to send them back anyway on principle and try to find a replacement that actually meets the original specs. It seems shady that someone would be trying to pass these off as proper BT-446 replacements.

product_title: EcoBox 2.0Mil 2-Inch x 110 Yards Clear Tape
review_headline: Pleasantly surprised given the price point and amount of product.
review_body: I was a little concerned about purchasing this product due to a few poor reviews but I needed some packing tape that was strong but not heavy heavy duty.  I have previously used some thin packing tape before only to end up frustrated with yards of shredded wads of split tape whose only use seemed to be for cats to pounce on and swat around the room  as I was trying to tape up a box.  So I was hoping that this product wouldn't give me the same result.  I've only used two of my six rolls but so far I have to say I'm pleased with the quality of this product given the amount of tape and its price point.  I haven't had any split or shredded tape.  It has stuck easily to my cardboard boxes and it has stayed stuck in both warm and cold as well as dry and humid weather.  My review is for the 2.0 mil thick tape which is NOT heavy duty but it's not ridiculously thin either, it's a nice in between thickness that for me has done the trick which for me is to wrap up larger sized cardboard boxes to ship out medium sized artwork.  It's important to me that the product arrive intact but then again I'm not interested in spending $$ just on tape. The Ecobox tape I purchased was a 110 yards of tape vs a number of competitors rolls which are size at half the amount of tape but not half the price.  So based on cost savings plus performance of the tape I definitely will buy the product again when I do not need the super heavy duty thick packing tape. Next time I need heavy duty tape I might check out the same manufacturer's heavy duty offerings since this 2.0 mil tape has definitely met my expectations.

product_title: TaoTronics Handheld Mobile Portable Document scanner 1050 DPI 1.44'TFT Colour & Mono, Color Display (For Photo, Reciepts, Books,JPG/PDF Format Selection, Micro SD Card required)
review_body:
The TaoTronics TT-DS001 Handheld Scanner is a smart and portable scanner. The device is made out of plastic but feels durable in the hand. I have never used a handheld scanner before and always took my scans with my smartphone. To get started just turn on the scanner, set the time and date, insert the micro SD card, calibrate the scanner and you are ready to go. The manual is quite useful to figure out all of these problems.
Handheld scanning has quite a learning curve and don't be disappointed when the first scans come out distorted. To get the perfect outcome you need to move both sides of the scanner at the same speed. If you are moving to quick a warning appears on the display. The page you are scanning has to lie on a flat surface in order to receive the best outcome. It is impossible to to get a good result from books, magazines etc. since it is impossible to make them perfectly flat. Pages smaller than A4 a hard to scan since they move during the scanning process and distort the outcome. Black-and-white A4 scans at 300 DPI take around 5 seconds. Color scans take longer. The higher the desired resolution the slower you have to move the device. The built in battery takes around 2 hours to charge and so far I was not able to fully drain it. The included CD contains ABBYY FineReader Sprint 9.0 OCR software for Windows. The software easily transformed the scanned JPG into a Word document. As used from other OCR software there were minor misreadings but overall the text was usable.
Overall I am very happy with the scanner and I was happy to finally try out a handheld scanner. This is a useful device when on the go but at home or in the office I would always prefer a stand alone solution. Hope I was able to help you with your purchase decision.

product_title: Five Star Locker Organizer, Magnetic Dry Erase Board and Locker Light, Color Will Vary (81048)
review_headline: Magnetized locker light, challenging battery install and a bit awkward to use (at least in my locker)
review_body:
I chose this for the locker light as I don't need the dry erase component. The marker pen is independent and does not attach to the board in any way. It has a magnet to attach to your metal locker.

My cube locker is very narrow and dark. This is a useful light but does require that I reach in and hit the button, which is awkward. The item came with no instructions but it was fairly intuitive to figure out that the back panel needed to come off to install the 3 AAA batteries ( not included). It takes a tiny Phillips head screw driver and some patience to get the back off. I'm not looking forward to doing that very often.

This item does give me some LED light in a useful form. If it was self activated or was easier to install the batteries I'd rate it higher.

product_title: VentMask Vent Register Filters
review_headline: GARBAGE! THE WORST PURCHASE I HAVE EVER MADE ON AMAZON.COM
review_body: I purchased these so call vent filters to filter the dust and pollen my wife suffers from these allergies. I purchased 3 packs to cover all my vents. First They do not stay on the vents you need to add tape to keep them on the vents and even then they do not stay completely on. Next they hinder the air flow of the vents and you will get moisture build up in the walls and ceilings. My normally hard ceiling is now soft and wet. This is the worst purchase I have ever made on Amazon.com. I will never buy from this vendor again.

product_title: Alvin PRESTIGE™ Studio Art Portfolios
review_headline: Makes it easier to travel for every artist
review_body:
I purchased the 17"x 22" portfolio and was pleasantly surprised upon its arrival. The portfolio is made of a plastic material. The handles move allowing for an easier carry and are ergonomically correct especially with the finger indentations. Inside you will find a if found please return card holder. There is an elastic clip to hold your basic drawing board and or paper. On the opposite side of the folio you will find a clear plastic casing with a zipper that is attached at the top to hold pencils, brushes , and any other utensil needed. Below the case you will find a pocket for rulers, larger sketch pads, or even completed work. They have created a much easier way for an artist on the go to be more efficient as I always seem to pack more than I can carry on my excursions. All in all I would highly recommend this product.

I received this product at a discounted price for my unbiased review.

product_title: FreeKey System
review_headline: Looks Innovative But Not As Good In Use
review_body:
This isn't what I wanted at all and I don't like it. The product description intrigued me, as did some of the positive reviews, so I ordered it thinking it would work well. I should have passed it by. I need quick release pull apart key rings so that I can detach the mailbox key while my car key is in the ignition with the motor running. This doesn't do it. I bought another set of detachable pull-apart key rings to handle that and will use it instead. That solution is also an easy way to separate keys to give to the valet or mechanic. Even easier than with this gizmo.

In addition, as was expressed in the review above by brh, I found that my keys sit at odd angles and do take up more room than necessary with this product. I also had a hard time keeping similar keys straight, as they would tend to migrate through the large ring and get out of order. My house key would even get stuck part way through the large ring and be hard to free up when I wanted to use it half the time. This product seemed like an interesting idea to me, but failed in actual use.

review_headline: Fairly sturdy, decent quality. Not too bad for the price in comparison
review_body:
Pretty good quality and quite sturdy, considering it's of Chinese manufacturing. A bit overpriced in my opinion ($33.49),, although for some reason all monitor stands seem to be. The attachment lip (which it essentially hangs the monitor bracket from) is however a rather poor imprecise fit, lending to insecure rotational maladjustment. Also would recommend felt pads to avoid its inherent desktop scratching (it comes without them).

Others mentioned the inability to hold the screen without downward droop. Yes, you do have to tighten the hex bolts very heavily. My largest monitor is 11.5 pounds. Anything much heavier may indeed pose too much weight for its mounts.

product_title: 3M Gel Wrist Rest for Keyboard - Designer Series Green
review_headline: Very Comfortable to Use, Stylish, But Had Issue With Image Peeling
review_body:
I bought this to use at work after growing tired of the plain, square mousepad they provided me with and also my wrist being sore after a long day in front of the computer. Since I've been using this mousepad with the very comfortable gel wrist rest, my wrist no longer is sore by the end of the day. The gel wrist rest has a slightly squishy feel to it, but is firm enough that it truly supports your wrist and allows you to glide your wrist over the mousepad smoothly and without sticking to your skin.

The beach scene is peaceful and gives me something pleasant to think about while I'm dealing with customers all day. The colors are vibrant and the size is perfect, not taking up too much space on the desk, but large enough that you have plenty of space on which to move the mouse. I also like that underneath it has a rubbery surface so that the mousepad doesn't slide around on the desk as you are working.

My only complaint is that on the top portion of the mousepad where the palm tree is, apparently the image is a large sticker overtop of the gel base because after a few days of using it, some of it started to peel up, so the construction on that portion could be better. I rectified this issue with a little super glue, so overall it's well made, very comfortable to use, stylish and well worth the bargain price!

product_title: THE ATLANTIS GLOBE
review_headline: Really a great aid to understanding our world
review_body:
We keep this globe right beside the dining table on the sideboard because it provides instant information on places being discussed, or mentioned in the news. This globe is nicely finished and the type is very readable, and mountains are indicated through extrusions. It's very useful that it has two axes of rotation so that countries in the far north and far south can be better scrutinized. Sure, one can pull out an atlas or Google maps, but a globe gives an understanding that two dimensional maps do not.

But the price (now $96 by this vendor) has risen faster than inflation. I paid $66 including S&H in 2012, and felt that even that price was pretty steep.

However. we have often consulted the globe during conversations at table about international events and military actions, so all in all, it has been a very worthwhile purchase.

too long. they don't fit into the standard length partition in a wallet. i made mine fit by cutting off the last 1/8th inch of the sealed end of the card holder. they should have done it that way from the outset. if both ends are open, the card is more easily extracted. push on the credit card using the indent, viewed here on the right end of the sleeve, and slide the credit card out the trimmed end. when i was done, the sleeve was exactly as long as the credit card.

product_title: HSM shredstar X6Pro
review_headline: Not worth the box it comes in
review_body:
I was fully prepared to give this shredder a three-star review, despite deducting two stars for the fact that the CD/DVD shredding doesn't come anywhere NEAR the 1/8" x 3/8" particle size advertised. But then the fourth time I turned it on and tried to feed something through it, the shredder began running constantly, sporadically blinking the "Bin Full" light (the paper in the bin was less than three millimeters deep), and refusing to feed any paper through. It goes without saying that we will be returning this shredder and purchasing one from a different manufacturer.

The good news is that if you are more fortunate than I, and your shredder survives for more than five minutes of use, it does a great job on paper--at least based on the single sheet that I was able to feed through it before it stopped working. The 1/8" x 3/8" shred size is as advertised, and it's the quietest shredder I've ever used. No manual was included, but it's not like a shredder is especially complicated to figure out. Still, it's an omission that I find remarkable, particularly at this price point.

That said, we purchased this shredder for use at my workplace in order to comply with our media destruction policy, which specifies a certain acceptable shred size for recordable CDs and DVDs. I selected this shredder in large part because of its advertised micro cut shred size. I was extremely disappointed when I shredded a CD and discovered that, while the shredded pieces are of varying sizes and some are quite small, some of them measured more than 3.75" x 1". Because there was no separate shred size listed for the CD shredder, nor any mention made of different capabilities in the product descriptions I've seen, I assumed that the CD shred size would be as advertised. Don't make the same mistake! Better yet, spare yourself the mistake of purchasing this product in the first place and look to another manufacturer instead.

product_title: Pilot Parallel Calligraphy Pen Set, 1.5 mm, 2.4 mm, 3.8 mm and 6 mm with Bonus Ink Cartridge (P9005SET)
review_body:
I have all four of these pens in my possession and they have a number of flaws.

1. There is no converter for these pens. What Pilot misleadingly labels "converter" is actually a rubber bladder for cleaning only. The packaging states very clearly "Converter* (for cleaning pen unit)". However, this is not visible in the advertised picture, and in my opinion Pilot should be ashamed of itself for calling a cleaning bladder a converter.
2. The supplied ink is very very wet. My guess (and it is only that) is that this wet ink is required because of the parallel plate design. However, because the ink is so wet, one does not obtain a good contrast between thick and thin lines because wet ink spreads too much making the thinest link too thick for my taste. I am doubtful that drier (more traditional) inks could be used but this is informed speculation.
3. The pens and packaging are cheaply made in my opinion. In fairness, this is reflected in the price.
4. The packaging is flimsy, and more importantly, it cannot be used to store a pen containing ink because the package cannot receive a capped pen. Moreover, the packaging is not easy to open or to reuse. I had to open the surrounding clear plastic box with a razor, trim off both ends of the clear plastic with scissors, and repurpose the plastic cover as a sleeve -- all for nought, since the assembled pen can't be place back in the packaging anyway.
5. The tip cannot affix to the body of the pen when it is in use. The tapered body is much smaller than the cap. Moreover, the cap is threaded rather than press fit to the pen. This is probably required (again, my guess) due to the fact that the ink is so wet a threaded seal is required to keep too much water from evaporating and clogging the parallel leaves.

In short, I am disappointed with the wetness of the ink, the quality of the pen, and the quality of the lines it generates. I didn't give the pens a 1-starrating however, because I think the price -- less than $7 each, mitigates the value engineering. Notwithstanding, I would rather pay more for a higher quality pen.

review_body: Pretty good and looks nice. Had it about a month and no problems with any size stack of papers that I ordinarily staple (and I'm a teacher preparing handouts for classes) besides my home and personal receipts and documents. Staples are the regular size and easy to put in. No jamming. It's taken a while to learn exactly where to put the papers in to get the staple where I want it. Very stable. Doesn't rock or move around much from use but it does slide backward on the desk fairly easy when I push books and others things around on the desk. That could be a plus if you want to move it around easily. Remember that you need a place to plug it in. My desk faces an open space as people come in the door to my office and the cord hanging down is a little unsightly. But, hey, it's a home office. And it's not like I didn't know it had a cord. I surely didn't want a battery operated one. Came well packaged and protected and on time. I guess the only reason I didn't rate it 5 stars is I can't get that excited about a stapler.

This is my third LD cartridge, though, for two different HP LaserJets (one model P3005dn and one 1320), and all three have worked flawlessly.  The printers accept them as "Genuine HP"; the page print is impeccable, with no streaking, gaps, or excess carbon; and the capacity is as least as good as an HP OEM cartridge. I'm delighted with the LD remanufactured toner cartridges I've bought, in all aspects.

product_title: Crane & Co. Engraved Ladybug Correspondence Card (CC3504)
review_headline: Crane Hand Engraved Ladybug Boxed Correspondence Cards
review_body:
These are some of my favorite Crane Correspondence Cards ... These are hand engraved Ladybug design on a Pearl White card with a Kid Finish ~ *roughly* 4' x 6.5" ... The Ladybugs themselves aren't that big :o) ~ At the widest part of their body they are maybe 6.5mm - 7mm ~ from the bottom to their head is maybe 8mm - 9mm including antennae. It's just large enough to be 'decorative' without being intrusive, IMO. It is a 'heavy' correspondence card ~ 96lb weight ~ it's part of what makes it so very nice. Ladybugs are said to be a symbol of luck, love, and protection ...

The envelope is lined in red ~ not a 'bright' red ~ more like a 'fire engine red'.

100% Cotton Paper - 100% Crane quality. Made in the U. S. A.

I will tell you - I am 100% partial to Crane paper products :o) I absolutely love them. I don't work for them or anything - I just love great paper because I send a lot of personal correspondence ... Yes, they cost a little more than other stationery ~ you get what you pay for. It's definitely worth it. People will want to know what / who / where. Don't let them down :o) ;o)

product_title: Ecoqua Notebooks and Journals
review_body:
While the pages eventually come flying out, I've found this very helpful as a professional designer. I move across several projects in a day and manage a team of designers. After I sketch, my pages can easily be taken out and put into project folders or scanned. NOT having the pages come out easily from most other sketchbooks is a problem for me. Putting project notes into a book that is bound means that to find the notes for one project, I have to dig through the notes of many other projects. So for me, most bound sketchbooks defeat multiple project organization. Additional attributes that I like:
-the dot matrix allows me to include or ignore a grid while I am drawing in a way that I can't with traditional grid lined paper
-the cover colors are excellent [so you'll see this same review under the other colors I use]
-the texture of the cover feels nice to the hand

For what it's worth, I design cross-platform interfaces and develop digital product strategies. All of that work goes into these books.

WARNING: The pages are A4, NOT 8.5 x 11. So a page is just a bit larger than a standard file folder. See the photo I've attached. I use standard file folders and live with it, but I ding it one star for this.

product_title: Avery Big Tab Write-On Dividers for Classification File Folders, 2-hole top punched at the Top of each Page
review_headline: Plenty of Space to Customize Tabs
review_body:
This write-on 5-tab divider for classification folders is a heavy duty cardstock with reinforced holes. They hold up well to the up and down motion of checking paperwork. They also hold up well to the riggers of adding paperwork to the classification folder. If you've ever worked with classification folders, you know the metal prongs that hold the paperwork and dividers in place can wear away at the holes in the dividers with consistent use. Because the holes are reinforced with copper, they are more durable and hold up to more wear.

The dividers themselves are a matte cardstock, so you can write/print on them. These side tabs are large and blank which allows plenty of space to customize the tabs. Unlike the narrow bottom tabs, these tabs stick out from the folder a bit on the side. While these folders are well made and easy to customize, I found that the tabs tended to get messed up a bit due to them sticking out of the folder.

product_title: Wilson Jones Heavy Duty Round Ring View Binder with Extra Durable Hinge, 2 Inch, Customizable, Bright Pink (W363-44-212)
review_headline: Nothing more than an average binder
review_body:
My kid had to have several 2-inch binders in specific colors, and I bought three of this "strongest" brand hoping for better durability. On first glance, I don't see anything about these binders that suggests they're any better than the ones found in any grocery or office supply store. I feel pretty confident that I will be contacting the manufacturer to claim the 1-year guarantee when these binders break down.

Description says the polypro cover lasts 10x longer, yet there was already a rip starting in the corner when I took the [[ASIN:B00CPXFMZ8 Yellow Binder]] out of the box (see photo). The cardboard of the binder cover is quite stiff, but thinner than others I have (there is a note on the binder that it uses less plastic to be environmentally friendly). The round rings on the inside are attached to the back cover, not the spine; I do like that because the papers lay flat when the binder is both open and closed.

The 1-year guarantee shows: "ACCO Brands proudly stands behind our products. If you are not satisfied with the performance of this Wilson Jones product, simply contact customer service at 800-541-0094 within 1 year of purchase. With the original proof of purchase and we will gladly replace the product at our expense." Also, this binder comes in numerous shades, priced randomly; if you don't need specific colors then shop around for the cheapest color.

product_title: Sailor Pen iron sword tree Standard fine print 10-2545-220 (japan import)
review_headline: it took me a few days to really love this pen
review_body:
I admit, it took me a few days to really love this pen. Initially, I was actually a little disappointed. The pen has written perfectly from the beginning, and the wood is gorgeous, BUT the plastic grip section of the pen feels very cheap in comparison; especially compared to the less expensive Sailor 1911 Standards and such. The plastic has obvious manufacturing seams, from the injection molding process, and I think that for a pen at this price point, those should NOT be visible. They can even be felt, if you run your hands along them at the right place.

However, once I got past the section, and began to evaluate the pen as a whole, I enjoyed it immensely. The pen has fantastic balance, posts well, and the wood is amazing. I would guess it is Bombay Blackwood, also known as Indian Rosewood. I am no expert on wood though. All I know is that the grain on the pen is gorgeous; it's hard to do a wooden pen well, but Sailor managed. The nib wrote very smoothly, with a touch of feedback (like most Sailor nibs, this writes how velvet feels). Evaluated as a package, it feels well crafted and like a high quality product. The name "Sailor Precious Wood" does not seem like hyperbole when I'm writing with this pen. It would have gotten a five out of five if the section plastic were better. There appears to be some sort of coating/lacquer/something on the pen that serves as protection from the elements, moisture, and apparently posting.

I would recommend the pen at this price, and also at it's full price, but ONLY if you like wood. High quality wooden fountain pens aren't as common as one might think, and this is a well executed example. I will probably sand down the seams of the injection molded section to enjoy the pen more, but even if I did not, the pen is just wonderful enough that I would still recommend it despite that flaw.

review_body:

As far as I can tell after several hours of monkeying around with this program, theres no way to make a report with notes or description field. Pretty critical if you as me.

Also it is very slow, or never senses the receipt paper.

It has a hell of a time figuring out the simplest of things like the difference between 9s and 4s.

So you will spend all day "fixing" and manually reentering all this information. In other words, how much time are you really saving?

No thanks, I will go back to using my camera-based scanner app... and its free!

product_title: Epson T252XL220 DURABrite Ultra Cyan High Capacity Cartridge Ink
review_headline: Great If The Price Is Right
review_body:
There are two ways to look at this cartridge, money and convenience.

The standard cart = 350 pages
The XL cart = 1100 pages
The XL cart has just over triple the amount of ink in it. So it would take just over 3 std sized cartridges to equal one XL. At current prices, the standard is $18 and the XL is $46. To print the same number of pages with a standard cartridge it would cost $56. The XL is about $10 cheaper. Multi-Packs (black ink plus three color cartridges) make the equation a lot more complicated.

Convenience could be a bonus with this cartridge. And it does factor into the cost. Changing cartridges is not terribly difficult, it takes about two or three minutes. It is still work, and if you are in the middle of printing a project, this could be a pain. Changing cartridges also wastes a lot of ink with the remaining cartridges. This printer pumps a lot of ink through all the cartridges when one is changed. So changing one cartridge might end up emptying another cartridge.

This cartridge is huge. The standard cartridges are really narrow. This big wide cartridge fills the left side of the ink holder in the printer.

Epson ink is outstanding. My Workforce printer produces excellent black and white documents and beautiful photographs even though it is not a photo printer.

At the right price, this is an outstanding cartridge.

product_title: Avery Printable Fabric for Inkjet Printers, 8.5 x 11 Inches, Pack of 5 (03384)
review_body: Ordered this iron-on fabric to make labels for the back sides of my wool applique work.  Had some reservations as to whether it would stick to wool felt and wool fabric, but for lack of a better option when it came to labeling the work I went ahead and ordered.  The 'fabric' arrived quickly and in typical Avery fashion was of high quality.  Logged into the Avery website and used their formats and printed my logo and info on one sheet, printing it out in a business card format, making ten labels per page.  The fabric printed clear and clean - impressive.  The next step was the iron-on aspect - not disappointed there either.  The label ironed on to the back of the wool felt without any issues using a hot iron.  The label remained adhered to the wool felt and appears that it would be next to impossible to remove - just want I wanted.  Next I ironed one on to the back of a piece of felted wool and again the label stuck without issue and appears to be stuck for the duration - again perfect!  I did use a hot iron but covered the label with a scrap piece of cotton fabric then ironed it to the wool felt so as to avoid leaving any iron marks on the back of the wool felt.  The fabric is somewhere in the medium weight range, but still flexible.  I cannot say I would use it on a cotton tee shirt as it might be too heavy for that, but for quilt label making it is outstanding.  Overall this iron-on fabric performed just as I needed it to go and I will certainly order again without hesitation.

product_title: HQTelecom.com Landline Call Blacklist Blocker with Extra Large LCD Display, Blue Blacklight, Dual Self Powered, Incoming Call Alert Flashing Light
review_headline: This works much better than the previous one that I got from Amazon
review_body: This works much better than the previous one that I got from Amazon. The best thing is that you can block the number after the fact. If an unwanted call comes in while you are gone, you can block it later when you get home. Also if you are home and the block unit is in another room, you can go to it later and call up the number you want to block from the down button, and then block it and see that it has been done. With 1000 number blocking, wish I had had that years ago. I have a Panasonic Phone System that allows 250 numbers to be blocked and went through them in less than a year. You can never have a great enough capacity if you have a land line phone. I already have about 34 blocked. I can always go back to the ones from several months ago and if it looks like they haven't called, erase them a make room for more robo calls.

product_title: VESA Mount Adapter Bracket for AOC i2367Fh/Fm/F, i2757Fh/Fm, i2067f, and i2267Fw/Fwh - by HumanCentric
review_headline: VESA adapter is functional and does as described. The ...
review_body:
VESA adapter is functional and does as described. The issue is though however when one has a DVI cable with any girth, it doesn't fit well at all.

I had two options: (1) Have the monitors tilted all the way forward to allow the most space between the monitor and VESA plate or (2) use a Dremel to cut back part of the plate to allow the VESA to be flushed against the monitor.

All-in-all, it's a high quality unit but may require a little modification to make work. I have an 8 monitor setup so it was quite abut of work to get functional.

The product owners sent an email about how to resolve the issue but the standard DVI cables for the AOC monitor were much bigger than the instructions suggested would fit.

review_headline: Color true to what was seen on line. No packaging issues as noted by others. Good quality. Highly recommended!
review_body:
My wife needed a Neon Green paper for something at work. Searched around, but the neon papers were priced very high. Found the Neenah Astrobrights in Martian Green. On screen, it looked very neon-like. I guess my Mac & its screen depict colors well, because what we received was exactly as it appeared online: Neon Green.

We typically use 20 LB. weight paper in our printer, but the heavier stock works even better for my wife's needs and works well in out HP printer. We may have found this elsewhere, but we would likely have searched for quite a while & almost certainly would have paid more. Very happy with this purchase.

product_title: Kensington Underdesk Adjustable Keyboard Platform with Wrist Rest (K60067)
review_headline: Save your money for something better.
review_body:
Really wish I could give this a better review, but I just cant. On a good day it does what I need it to do, which is support my keyboard and mouse at a certain angle for my very tall desk. On any other day it tends to be an annoyance. Giving this two stars because there are a few good things about it, but only a few.

My main pet peeve is that it's not as sturdy as it needs to be. If I put any sort of weight on it, (like when I'm typing, or even using my mouse) It will slip and shift down to a lower position. It also bounces a bit when I type, but that's less of a irritation by comparison. If those two things weren't an issue, I wouldn't have a problem with this platform. It's wide enough to fit both my keyboard and mouse, which is awesome. The tray, albeit plastic, seems to be of a good quality, and it was also very easy to install, which is also a plus.

Overall, as tempting as the price is, save up for a higher quality keyboard tray. I'm going to upgrade as soon as I can afford to.

product_title: CPR V202 Call Blocker - Block All Robocalls, Political Calls, Scam Calls, Telemarketing Calls, Unwanted Calls On Landline Phones. Block All Nuisance Calls At The Touch Of A Button Using Caller Id
review_body: It works exactly as advertised. Very easy to set up. If you already have an answering machine or one built into your main landline phone, then you should buy an inexpensive phone line splitter from Walmart or Staples etc. and then follow the instructions that come with the Call Blocker. When my answering machine says "Unknown Caller", I just let it ring and wait until the caller hangs up. Then I press down the list of callers (the down arrow on the right), write down the number, go to my computer and google it. If you are certain that it was an unwanted call, go back to Call Blocker. Press down the down arrow on the right once again. When the display of the Call Blocker is showing the last caller that you just checked,  press the large button Block Now. In a couple of seconds, it would show Successful and that means that particular caller is blocked as long as you want. Simple. I have already blocked about 18 in two weeks and it is pleasantly quiet! This is a great product. I took away one star because this product is designed to be able to handle two separate main lines, identified as Line 1 and Line 2. In my unit, Line 1 is dead. Unresponsive. It took some time to understand that was the cause of my starting trouble.  Fortunately I have only one line in my home and so I just started to use Line 2. No problem.

review_headline: The quality on this scanner is great, however most people buy it for scanning film ...
review_body:
The quality on this scanner is great, however most people buy it for scanning film negatives and transparencies. For this purpose, it is a pain to use, the film loading is very frustrating. Some film types will simply not load.

Fuji Velvia 50 in Medium Format? Forget it. I purchased some anti-newton ring glass to try to help this problem, but it's still difficult.

I have found that it is much more worthwhile to simply pay for high quality scans from my photo lab. I'm keeping this scanner because it is fantastic for prints and the only option for scanning old negatives or slides at a reasonable price, but I hope that Epson or one of their competitors can find a better solution for loading and scanning film with these flat bed scanners.

product_title: Scribbler 3D Pen for Printing in the Air 3D Drawing Pen for Doodling Art Tool with 3 Loops of Plastic Filament Refills
review_body:
I've been looking at 3d pens for a while, and the version 2 and version 3 scribbler pens seemed to have more positive reviews than other brands, so I finally bought one (Ver2). Fresh out of the package, it sets up easily and I could begin playing with it right away. There is a definite learning curve. don't expect to get smooth, straight lines right away. Also, don't expect to be able to draw in three dimensions without a lot of practice. What the pen does well, is create solid or open work flat pieces that can then be joined together to create 3d models. as my first project I created a lacy, multi-colored visor and it came out fine. Some people reported issues with clogging or failing motors. I didn't experience this, but I've only been using it for a couple of hours.

Some things to be aware of:

I found that I had to put some slight pressure on the filament to get it to feed all the way to the nozzle. If I let go, it just stopped moving. Once it was all the way through, it worked fine. The reverse function is the same. Very slight pressure is needed to begin reversing the feed.

Even though the pen toggles between two speeds, the slow speed is pretty much useless, except for making tiny fingers for action figures (my second project. It is very, very slow. The fast speed is a little too fast to make smooth straight lines. I will probably improve at this with practice, as I get used to the pen, but I can see it being frustrating for first time users.

If you use the pen for more than 20-30 minutes, the filament can start to hang up. You need to turn the pen off and let it cool down before you continue. Also, if you change colors, the first 3 or 4 inches of the removed filament is too brittle to use after being heated in the pen, so you have to cut it off. This seems wasteful. If I decide to do a big project, I'll probably purchase a spool of filament from an office supply store, instead of the tiny packages sold for crafters.It's a lot cheaper that way.

The motor that feeds the filament sounds chintzy - exactly like a mosquito whining in a dark room when you're trying to sleep. This was annoying for about five seconds, but then I got caught up in what I was creating and ignored it.

Long story short - this is a toy, not a tool. If you manage your expectations, you'll be happy with it. If you want professional results, wait for the next generation of pens. They seem to be improving quickly based on consumer expectations.

review_headline: Great colors and a great set
review_body:
My students love these markers. We use them on windows, walls, tables, basically any cleanable surface. The Expo brand in particular is especially nice for doing window art. There is enough drag on the felt to keep the marker from wiggling, but not so much that it staggers. Even with heavy pressure, the felt does not degrade. Once on the surface, the ink does not blend very well, so filling in large chunks of space can look less than solid. The tips can also get pretty dirty, especially if they run over black ink.

One extra tip. If you are looking for cheap and effective whiteboards, go to Home Depot and get the melamine coated shower board. There are 2 types, one with a premium feel and a cheaper thinner kind. The cheaper one (which costs around $15 for a huge 6x4 sheet) is the one you want. They will even cut it for you there, so you can make many smaller board out of one larger one (though you will need to tape up the edges),

product_title: School Smart Vertical Pencil Sharpener, 6 x 4 Inches, Electric
review_headline: Sharpens great but really sad about durability of plastic
review_body: I would LOVE to give this pencil sharpener 5 stars.  It works fabulously...sharpens pencils quickly and with very sharp points and doesn't break them. My boys unpacked and set it up in the kitchen them moment arrived, and they both raved that it was even better than the ones in their classrooms at school. Here's the problem, though:  On the second day we owned it, my 8-year-old dropped it when he was taking it up to his bedroom, and the part that holds the shavings shattered into at least 5 pieces.  I know that the break was caused by our mistake, but I would think that a product specifically designed for children would be a little more durable than that.  I have super-glued the cup back together, and it will suffice, but it looks tacky and doesn't fit quite securely into the sharpener any more, so I'm not sure how reliably my son will be able to close it securely after emptying.

product_title: AmazonBasics 12-Sheet High-Security Micro-Cut Paper
review_body: My old shredder finally croaked, bills that needed shredding were piling up so I decided to give this guy a try.  Reviews don't lie; this is an excellent shredder and super bang for the buck, especially if you consider the competition from Fellows, or those sold at Staples and Costco.  It's "only" $100 for a high capacity micro-cut shredder.  The paper tub is big enough that you don't need to keep on emptying it so often. You cannot find these specs elsewhere for $100.  Rolling wheels are nice.  I have this shredder tucked in a corner and only bring it out when needed.  Credit cards are no problem. I also shred about 20 CD-RW discs... The shredder ate them like Cookie Monster. Chomp chomp chomp. But the crunching noise was EXTREMELY loud. I think on occasion, it's okay but I would not regularly crunch CDs with this. I would think it will weaken the motor and blades if you do it too much.  The 2 cons I can think of compared to my older shredder is that: 1. Speed is quite slow. If you have a big pile, it will take you awhile. But I'm fine with it b/c I believe you're getting micro-cut for trading speediness. 2. The top does not come off. My old shredder was the type that attaches to the top of a bucket and you'd need to remove the top piece to empty out the shreds. I actually didn't like this and like the drawer setup of this shredder. That said, it would be quite difficult to reach in and pull out stuck pieces of paper should that ever happen.  Someone commented about the weird angle which you have to insert the paper... the opening is at an angle but it's not an issue for me.  Overall, I'm very happy with this purchase.  As for maintenance, you can find various discussions online that the $10/bottle shredder oil is nothing but canola oil being marked up like 100x. Some will say that it's a reformulated version suited for shredders while others say it's the same oil you use in cooking. I went cheap and used the cooking oil for maintenance... will see over time if that is good or detrimental.

The small instruction is not clear enough (at least for me) to indicate clearly the position of the small notch in the base of the needle. This is crucial for the tag gun to work properly. After figuring out what is the proper way of inserting and securing the needle, I loaded gun with a bunch of tags and I tested the gun. Initially on the very delicate, thin silk fabric and later, very thick, heavy cotton fabric. In both cases, the needle penetrated both without any problem leaving almost invisible small hole. As summary: It worked perfectly.

product_title: E-More® Super Silence K3 2.4G Wireless Keyboard Chocolate Keyboard For DESKTOP PC Laptop (Pink)
review_headline: Sleek, Stylish, and Comfortable to Use
review_body: I absolutely LOVE this wireless keyboard. I sit on the couch while on the computer because my computer is hooked up to a 46" television. I like to be comfortable and I hate dealing with a big bulky keyboard. This is just what I needed. It's very slick, stylish, thin, comfortable, and it's pink! It's extremely easy to set up. Simply hook up the wireless adapter to a USB port on your computer, your computer will automatically download the drivers for the keyboard, and then it's ready to use! I love that it comes with a dust cover as I have two dogs and a cat that shed constantly. Now when I'm not using the keyboard I can keep it protected from dust and pet hair.  The keys aren't "super silent" but they are a lot quieter than my Logitech keyboard. With the provided dust mat the keys do become much quieter! So I can use the mat to keep my keyboard clean or to silence the keys a little bit. This is truly an awesome keyboard at a very affordable price. I definitely recommend it! *discount received for testing and review*

review_headline: It's a good sized desk organizer for the price
review_body:
It's a good sized desk organizer for the price. Holds a lot of stuff. I actually have a couple spots still available for items to be put in it, but not sure what to put in it, haha. I like that it has a drawer! I was reading other reviews before debating on whether to purchase it or not and an uneven drawer was something to be careful about. Thankfully, mines was easy to pull out and push back in, however overall the structure of the caddy was uneven and looks poorly put together. It's unnoticeable from afar, but if you really examine it, it can be quite bothersome (especially if you're "ocd" like me). Also since it's metal, beware with sliding it across the surface of your table or accidentally pushing it or whatever. I took the advice of another customer that bought this and put felt or some sort of thick cloth to protect the table's surface from being scratched up by my caddy. :)
Don't know if I'd recommend it, but for the price, I don't see why not. It's worth a try!

Honestly, I feel a bit silly with such as thick reel hanging from my lanyard. I am hoping to find something a bit thinner (yet still functional) once this reel finally breaks. Until then, I will stick with it.

review_headline: NOT WORTH A PIG WALLERING iN CRAP
review_body: My changer just stop working for my Samsung S5.  I haven't ordered from Amazon for quiet some time.  I was surfing the Web one night when I noticed the the charger that I ordered.  A 6 ft long heavy duty charger.  I was so anxious to get it in the mail.  My anxiety didn't last very long. I'm extremely handicapped and  my anxiety didn't last very long. product_title: Epson Duet 80-Inch Dual Aspect Ratio Projection Screen
review_headline: Just what I was looking for
review_body:
The form factor to this product is fantastic. There are a few issues that I can comment on below...

1) My problem is that I travel and I want to take this with me. My solution was to use a hard shell golf bag with wheels. You can check the bag into most airlines without a problem. The Duet Dimensions are 46.2 x 12.2 x 9.3 inches. A typical card shell golf bag has a total height of 51 inches, total interior height 47.5 inches, total interior width 11 inches, and total interior depth at 12.5 inches. This easily fits the Duet requirements. I usually wrap the Duet in a towel to prevent a lot of movement in the case. You can buy a used hard shell case for $40 is you look around.

2) When I first stretched out the Duet, I noticed a wrinkle down the center of the screen (see the photo). I was a little concerned about it. I decided to leave the screen open for a while to see what would happen. The wrinkle dissipated enough within a day to be OK.

3) The issue with the height of the screen has been mentioned before. It would be handy if the height was several inches taller, but that would extend the overall folded dimensions of the product (and no longer fit in my golf bag). Fortunately, the top of the tripod has a plastic guide that easily comes off. For the times I need the screen to be a little taller, I take the guide off and insert another pole down the shaft of the tripod. It took some looking to find a suitable size. I will post a photo the next time I have this set up.

Overall, it is a great product and meets my needs at a great price...

product_title: iCraze Adjustable iPad Laptop Table Laptop Computer Desk Portable Bed Tray Book Stand Multifuctional & Ergonomics Design
review_headline: Great for Laptops, not so great for fighting Zombies.
review_body:
Presuming you're not trying to weaponize this device for bashing in the skulls of the undead, this is a really useful device. As a Zombie fighting weapon, Id give this pretty low marks. It's far too blunt and lightweight to deliver any sort of serious damage to a horde of lifeless zombies heading in your direction.
But, as a means of propping up a laptop computer, it's really well done. It's small enough to carry to a meeting where they're not going to provide a standing desk for you. But super versatile. I've used it on a normal table, a kitchen counter, and also sitting on the couch so your legs to get hot fromt he laptop. bonus is the 2 USB powered fans. I had to glue on a few strips of neoprene foam I had laying around to create a bit of airflow under the laptop, otherwise the fans can't really do much. But with that little addition, they're doing great. not too noisy

What I wish is that they'd give you some settings (each of the three adjustment points has degree numbers so that you can remember your settings). I've taken to taping the settings to the inside leg so I can just go from there for different applications.

Overall, a well made (not super solid, it's light gauge aluminum after all) unit. the joints are all plastic but seem to hold just fine w a 15" Macbook. I'm not sure it's really worth $40, but I can't find a better price. It also came with a little side tray, too small for a mouse pad, I use it for a place to have my iPhone handy while I'm working.

product_title: SOL Corp (Non-OEM) 2 Pack REFILL KIT for use in Brother TN-450 TN450 Toner for HL-2230 HL-2240 HL-2240D HL-2270DW
review_headline: FANTASTIC PRICE, GOOD QUALITY, AND HERE'S A TIP TO HELP YOU STAY CLEAN
review_body: When I was a young man, I paid nearly $50 for the manufacturer's replacement cartridges.  Then, I grew up and started buying "compatible" cartridges at around $18 each.  Now, I am older and wiser, and I use these refill kits at a cost of about 5 bucks apiece.  As the old saying goes, we get too soon old, and too late smart.  MY SECRET TO SUCCESS (AND CLEAN HANDS) IS SIMPLE:  Buy yourself a large plastic kitchen funnel (they're about 5 bucks at your local market) and use that to pour the toner into your old cartridge.  The nozzle on these bottle caps is much too small.  I fill the cartridges over a trash can, so I don't care if a little toner spills.  (Also: bring a couple of wet paper towels or napkins with you, so you can wipe the kitchen funnel -- and your hands -- clean before you go back in the house.)  I have used several refills so far, and absolutely NO PROBLEMS WITH MY PRINTER.  (The toner light stays on, but who cares?)  At this price --- and with the amount of printing that I am doing --- I could buy a new printer every month, and I'd still be saving money.

product_title: VELCRO Brand  -  ONE-WRAP: For Cables, Wires & Cords - 45' x 1 1/2" Large Roll - Black
review_headline: Use for Clarinet and Sax Ligatures.
review_body: I'm using short lengths, trimmed a bit, as ligatures for clarinets and saxes.  These work great -- better than some very expensive ligatures.  This stuff is stiffer than regular velcro and no sewing hook tape to loop tape -- a single piece does it.  The only trick is that you wrap the velcro before you place the reed against the table.  Then slip the ligature off, place reed on the table and slip it back on.  It pushes down pretty snug.  You can easily make minor adjustments in the reed and I have not had the reed slip while playing.  More of the reed vibrates than with some other ligatures -- hence all the exotic designs out there.

product_title: AZ Supplies © Compatible Replacement Toner Cartridges for Brother TN-336 High Yield 4 Color Set TN336BK, TN336C, TN336Y, TN336M for use in Brother HL-L8250CDN; HL-L8350CDW; HL-L8350CDWT; DCP-L8400CDN; DCP-L8450CDW; MFC-L8650CDW; MFC-L8850CDW; MFC-L8600CDW Printers (Black, Cyan, Magenta, Yellow) Black: 4,000, Color: 3,500 Page Yield.
review_headline: which is clearly a poor quality recycled product of incorrect make
review_body:
I purchased Brother TN336 compatible NEW toner cartridges. I received a set that contained recycled Brother TN315 cartridges, with the TN315 label covered over by a cheap sticker. It seems that although TN315 will fit my printer drum, it is clearly not intended to take this because it is not recognized and no fill status is displayed on printer. I actually only discovered the discrepancy after noting the above and looking under the AZ label. What is also troublesome is that toner leaked profusely out of the cartridge when I first opened it, and there was no protective cover in place over the roller in the black cartridge, and the cover was not sealed.

The description below, clearly does not match the product, which is clearly a poor quality recycled product of incorrect make. Each of the cartridges were packaged individually in boxes labelled correctly as TN336, but clearly conceal that they are shipping TN315. I would hope this is just an isolated mistake and not the general practice of the company
Per item description "These units are manufactured 100% brand new with all new parts including OPC drums, wiper blades, a smart chip and other internal parts, they are an economical alternative to expensive OEM Brother TN-336 laser toner cartridges. The compatible toner cartridge will produce the same amount of page yield as an OEM cartridge would. This is a Compatible Brother TN-336"

product_title: DO NOT BEND Self Inking Rubber Stamp - Red Ink
review_headline: Not as smooth as the Ideal 4912, but ExcelMark has other perks that may be worth considering.
review_body:
This was our second ExcelMark stamp purchased from DiscountRubberStamps, both were somewhat perplexing experiences: We went with the ExcelMark brand, because we'd just purchased some ExcelMark red ink refill that was incompatible with our previous 2000Plus stamp (I don't think it was actually made to be refilled). When that didn't pan out we purchased a new "Fragile Handle with Care" ExcelMark stamp to ensure compatibility with the ink refill we'd already bought. The Fragile stamp came in perfect condition, but the box lid had been torn off prior to shipping, as it wasn't in amazon's shipping box either. We inquired, were told by DRS to contact amazon since they handled the shipping, indicating that it had gone straight from the factory to amazon and they never even touched it. Upon asking amazon what happened we were given a full refund and told to keep the stamp, even though we didn't request such or even imply dissatisfaction with the product, we just wanted to know why the box was torn open and if the instructions were missing, as there was nothing inside except the stamp, which appeared to be in perfect condition. We thought there might be some greater elaboration on how to flip the dual-sided ink pad than the rough diagram built into the product itself.

Happy with the Fragile stamp we received (MUCH better stamp than the 2000Plus model it replaced) we felt a little like we owed it to DRS to replace our Do Not Bend stamp with them too, since we were given an unnecessary refund on the previous Fragile stamp. The Do Not Bend stamp arrived quickly, shipped in a padded envelope. The box didn't have the lid torn off and unlike our Fragile stamp this one had a rubber DRS sticker on the side of the stamp. But this stamp came with a new oddity, the push instructions made into the plastic itself on the reversible inkpad tray was misprinted: It had "Push" embossed on the side that you can't push from and the nature of the stamps design prevents it from being pushed the other way, as well as prevents the possibility that the tray could have been inserted backwards, as there are locking tabs on one side that prevent that from being possible. It appears the mold for the tray itself must be defective, as strange as that seems. Frankly, if it wasn't such a cheap product, I would have assumed it to be a knockoff, enforced further by the screenprinted ExcelMark label being side by side rather than over/under like the one pictured and the absense of rubber feet, though our Fragile ExcelMark also doesn't have rubber feet like the one pictured seems to. Also worth noting is that one side of the ink pad also already needed re-inking, as it looked rather faded - which we indicated wasn't a problem, since we'd already bought the ink.

We again asked DRS what happened, figuring since they actually shipped the Do Not Bend stamp themselves they might be able to explain this curiousity. Again, we got a fast reply from the company. They agreed it was odd but offered no explanation, instead they offered to ship us another for free, telling us to keep both. This was IMO above and beyond what was required, as we had already expressed satisfaction with the quality of the stamp we received despite the presumed manufacturing defect that in no way hinders operation or functionality of the product.

When the replacement arrived, we were surprised to find inside a Do Not Bend stamp made by Ideal instead. Again we inquired, this time trying to be very clear that we were satisfied with the product so they wouldn't feel they needed to send us yet another one. And again we received a fast reply, basically thanking us for notifying us of their mistake and answering a follow-up question we had regarding whether or not the Excel Mark ink refill would work with the Ideal stamp too - which they indcated it would.

You can draw your own conclusions from this interaction. Personally, I'd have no qualms with ordering from DRS again, due to their customer service, despite the curious issues we've had with 3 our of 4 shipments from them.

As for this stamp itself, we love that you don't have to smash down hard to get it to ink uniformally unlike with our previous 2000Plus stamp bought from Staples. Even when the ink is low, it leaves a uniform impression without much pressure, only the ink looks faded when it's low. However, after receiving the Ideal stamp, we find that we like it even better. The mechanism just works so much smoother on the Ideal stamp, where the ExcelMark stamps seem to rub or catch in multple places as you depress them. The Ideal stamp actually has rubber feet too. I'm not sure of the purpose yet, but it does make it feel nicer.

The most obvious advantage to the Excel is that the ink pad can be flipped so you don't have to re-ink the pad as frequently or have to wait an extra minute while the ink soaks into the pad. I'm new to this type of re-inkable stamp, so I don't know if the inkpads themselves tend to wear out faster than the product. But having multiple inkpads on the device for when one wears out is really the only significant benefit I see to having a reversible pad, as it doesn't take much longer to re-ink a pad than it does to flip it. The hardest part is taking it in and out, which is relatively easy, though a bit clunky.

Both inkpads offer a nice clear lower for aligning the pad on the paper. It's probably not an issue for most applications, but the ExcelMark is even notched so you can even see the stamp rotate all the way down to the paper for potentially more precise placement if needed, since the casing is larger than the stamp itself. The Ideal stamp on the other hand obscures the pad as you stamp.

If you decide to go with this or the Ideal, be sure to get some ink refill. These type pads with their water-based ink really don't seem to be designed to last like a 2000Plus stamp. You'll need to re-ink the pad periodically. With the Excel, I've already felt compelled to re-ink it only after a few dozen stamps. Other reviews criticizing the ink for being faded or not lasting should also probably be ignored, as it seems the nature of this type of stamp, unlike the 2000 Plus stamps that last 1000 to 2000 stamps (the ones I've had started fading and stamping uneven after only 500 or so unless you hit it rather hard and/or rocked it back and forth, which just wears down the rubber even more) and then are apparently meant to be discarded.

Like the Ideal, the ExelMark uses a water-based ink, so it might smear on slick surfaces if it can't soak into the paper. Stamping on plain bright white printing paper it seems to dry instantly, or at least won't smear if I rub it mere seconds later. Don't expect it to stick to polymailers though, without gently covering it in clear tape.

My only disappointment - and my primary reason for not giving it a higher score - with the ExcelMark, as well as the Ideal DO NOT BEND stamps is that unlike our "Fragile Handle with Care" ExcelMark, the Do Not Bend writing doesn't attempt to maximize the size capacity either stamp is capable of. Both stamps, sold by DRS, produced a DO NOT BEND impression that were identical in size and font style. Indeed the stamp pads appear identical in every way. It's pretty clear that these are universal bodystyles with a large plate made to receive a variety of stamp pads of varying sizes and styles. Regardless, it was a bit disappointing that neither stamp pad was as large as the stamp body or pad plate were capable of holding, which seemed rather cheap, compared to our FRAGILE HANDLE WITH CARE ExcelMark stamp from DRS that clearly seems to be designed specifically for the size stamp plate it is being used on, where despite two lines of type, the word "fragile" uses a larger font than either Do Not Bend stamp does.

In thecase of the ExcelMark, looking at the DO NOT BEND pad on the pad plate, it appears the lettering could have been 50% larger - with the Ideal stamp it appears it could have even doubled in size, as the Ideal stamp has a bit larger body, and a wider and taller pad plate than the ExcelMark, making the stamp pad itself look rather small affixed to the sticky pad plate mount inside. I would have much preferred a more elongated font, like that pictured on the Ideal listing page, for a more noticable stamp. It's not that big a deal, but it is an area for improvement that would make the product seem significantly more professional, like the Fragile stamp does. The DO NOT BEND font on both stamps looks identical to the one pictured in this listing, pictured at the time of this review anyway.us stamp. You'll need to re-ink the pad periodically. product_title: HP DeskJet 1010 Printer (CX015A)
review_headline: Worst Product I've Probably Ever Bought
review_body:
There's no damn reason this product should have anything above a two-star overall rating. It is simply a product that doesn't work.

Opened the box, followed the "Instructions" which were all pictures, no text. Ran the software off the included CD and decided to test it out. Hmm, I wondered. Where's the cord that connects the printer to the computer? I looked twice in all the packaging, reread all the instructions....nothing. Wow, I said. It must be wireless. Tried to connect wirelessly, no luck.

HP SIMPLY DOES NOT INCLUDE THE CORD TO CONNECT IT TO COMPUTER.

I'm simply dumbfounded that a company can legitimately put out a product that will not work whatsoever unless you buy other accessories, and does not tell you so anywhere. It's not on the box, it's not in the descriptions, it's not on the instructions.

Let me make this crystal clear.

IF YOU BUY THIS PRINTER, YOU WILL NOT BE ABLE TO PRINT ANYTHING. That is, until you drive out to s a store somewhere and buy a....printer cord? I guess? At random? And hope it works.

Luckily, I found a cord in my bundle of crap that worked with the printer. Guess what? Printer still doesn't work.
Went to HP's help site. They said to download the latest drivers. Did that. Still doesn't work.
Went back to HP's help site. They said to unplug it and plug it back in. Did that. Still doesn't work.

So, in conclusion, if you do not go out and purchase a separate printer cord, you will not be able to print with this printer. And evidently, according to HP's help site, this printer also will not work with Apple Computers.

None of this is listed in the instructions or product descriptions.

product_title: Nice Production INP-O Series Book Stand
review_headline: Saves my neck!  So convenient! Flawless so far.
review_body:
I love reading smaller paperback books, but grow tired of holding the pages open. I also notice that I get neck pain if I am looking down too long. At times I like to lay down on my side in bed with the book in front of me to help with this even though it is harder to hold open.

THIS IS THE SOLUTION!! First off, it is very high quality and you can tell that the person who designed it payed attention to detail. The construction is sturdy, and the little metal arms are very functional and solid. It holds the book wide open and the metal arms are so thin that they do not cover up the words as I read.

The stand in the back can go in many different angles, although I usually keep it flat since I do not read at a table. The best part for me is that, since I love underlining in my books, it is now very easy to do so with the arms holding the book for me! I love it!!

One piece of advice: buy a bigger one if you use bigger books. This works perfect for small to medium sized paperbacks (the smallest one), You might need a bigger one if you're reading bigger hardbacks, textbooks, cookbooks, etc

review_headline: This series looks and reads like a sturdy unit but it actually is very limited ...
review_body: This series looks and reads like a sturdy unit but it actually is very limited to only the lightest of loads. Disregard the 900 lb rating. Don't  even think of putting substantial weight on any one shelf. It is unstable. True it is easy to assemble but the boltless design leaves the shelf racking from side to side and the 3/8 particle board is flimsy. The posts and shelf supports are stamped from thin steel which contributes to the instability. If you are looking for something lightweight for sewing or light office duty you may be satisfied but I would caution anyone to look elsewhere first and definitely before buying a wholesale case. I will not buy again.

review_headline: Good if you want to save space (or for a cleaner look). Otherwise, just use a decorative trash can for your bags.
review_body: I used to store my plastic bags in small trash cans, but this is admittedly neater and saves space. If you're not used to having stainless, be warned it shows fingerprints and requires constant cleaning. Another thing I don't like is the roughness of the edges on the openings. They won't cut you, but it does hurt if your drag your hand across them, which my toddler often does when she is helping me pack the bags away. I was only able to store about half of my plastic bag 'collection' into the bin, so I'll probably need at least one more. One last thing I want to point out: this isn't designed to store the thicker plastic bags that you get from bookstores/toy stores. You could fit them in, but they won't compress down very well and so the capacity of the bin will be less than is stated in its description.

product_title: Headset Buddy PC Dual 3.5mm Headset to RJ9/RJ10 CISCO Phone Adapter (PC35-RJ9Cisco)
review_headline: Not Compatible with most Phones, Only CISCO
review_body: I bought this without reading the description carefully enough, not noting that it is specifically for a CISCO phone.  Needless to say I did not have luck using it on my non-CISCO phone.  However, I secondly then bought B005LKKNQA 01-PC35-RJ9A "PC Headset 01-PC35-RJ9A to RJ9/RJ10 Adapter - Dual 3.5mm to RJ9 Headset Adapter, Not RJ11" and  that DID work with my office phone from AT&T -- even though that phone is also not listed explicitly compatible with my phone.  So, if you don't have a CISCO phone, I would say do not buy this CISCO-specific adapter cable, rather try the second cable I bought. I'm using that for long-winded teleconference meetings, where it gets to be a pain sitting there for two hours holding a handset up to my ear -- much better with a headset -- I bought the Plantronics Audio 326 Stereo PC Headset.

product_title: Brother MFC8950DW Wireless Monochrome Printer with Scanner, Copier and Fax, Amazon Dash Replenishment Enabled
review_headline: Good for the first year, but now changed
review_body:
I own two for my business.
I would have originally given it a 4 or 5 star for the first year, and I originally liked it so much I bought the second one.
Customer support ranges from extremely helpful - replaced two year old fuser at their expense to extremely awful - basically accusing my employees of using a stolen printer. The big issue making it a one star now is that some sort of update is now causing the printer to think that all third-party toner cartridges are recognized as empty after a short amount of printing. Support will not provide any info about how to override this recent detection problem.
You can either refill using their cartridges at $100 each or switch printers now. Don't get me started on their $200 drum replacements. Of course, Brother will offer no help if they learn you use third party products (toner or drums at less than 1/3 the price). They refused to help with broken door on ADF tray after employees did not report this during the first year of use.

product_title: Brother DS-720D Mobile Duplex Color Page
review_headline: Not a bad quick low-profile scanner
review_body:
Not a bad quick low-profile scanner. The issue I mainly have with most scanners is the software. This scanner comes with a few options, PaperPort being the application I use primarily. Though it works well for what I need, there are constant TWAIN errors that pop-up which are annoying (running on Win 7). The software is definitely older (written for XP or prior), but this seems to be what you get with most scanner software unfortunately.

The only limitation that I have found as an annoyance so far is that the scanner/software hangs if the paper you are scanning is too long. I was trying to digitize a very long document (car purchase papers), but I could not change any setting that would allow the entire sheet to scan.

product_title: Epson Perfection V600 Color Photo, Image, Film, Negative & Document Scanner - Corded
review_headline: A nice working scanner for the money.
review_body:
I have not used a Flatbed scanner before so I have nothing to compare this with. I am pleased with the results having scanned a about 1000 slides.
My slides were 25 to 50 years old so many seemed drab as they apparently had lost some of their color brilliance. I regained some of the color but I am far from an expert in photoshopping. Bottom line, yes I am happy that I bought this Epson and did something with my slides rather than just let them sit in their carousels. I had no issues with installation of the info from Epson or Adobe.

product_title: RFID Blocking Sleeves & Credit Card Protector For Women & Men With Pocket Security For A Money Clip or Wallet to Stop Theft of Sensitive Information Stored On A Passport, ID & All Cards
review_headline: Love the quality of these sleeves
review_body:
Love the quality of these sleeves. I bought them to replace the paper RFID sleeves we were given by our bank. The sleeves are so well made that the I can tell it won't easily warp over time as I use it having to slip it out of the wallet each time I need my card.

I won't take a star away for this because this is not consistently true to all my wallets but the sleeve tends to make the card slot very snug or it won't fit at all like in my husband's wallet. However, it stays put on a money clip, and in my case, I put the sleeved card in the cash pocket (instead of a snug fit in the card slot).

As more and more institutions convert our bank and identification cards to have an RFID, products like these will always be an important item to have in our wallets. I recommend these to anyone and plan to buy more of these same ones as the need comes up.

product_title: 56x Souslife Chalkboard Labels.  Super Slick White Chalkboard Marker Included. 56 Reusable Labels With 8 Gorgeous Shapes and 2 Sizes. Use For Mason Jars / Glasses / Containers
review_headline: High-Quality, Large-Sized Chalkboard Labels, Marker Included
review_body:
These are very nice, decorative, yet useful, chalkboard labels. The set, which includes 56 labels of various shapes and sizes, also has a chalk marker pen that is small, but actually very nice and readable. (Some chalk markers have very wide and floppy tips that make it difficult to write clearly.)

The shapes are trendy and look very nice, and even the smaller set of labels leaves plenty of space to write on. These are great for labeling foodstuffs, toy tubs, gifts, office supplies, party games, etc. The possibilities are near endless.

They stick well to most surfaces, and are quite durable. Stuck on a glass jar, one stood up to frequent wipe downs, damp erasures and even a Windex spray clean without tearing or coming off.

I'm not sure about their "reusability" in terms of removing them, which is near impossible to do without ripping them, but they can be wiped off cleanly and rewritten at a later date fairly easily, and the sturdiness of the label means you can do this quite a few times before you'd need to replace it.

All in all, a good-looking, well-priced labeling solution.

*FULL DISCLOSURE: I received a sample of the product in exchange for an honest review*
