product_title: Brother HL3170CDW Wireless Color  Printer
review_body: It prints and the quality is decent.  However, whenever it goes into a deep sleep, the wireless turns off and the entire printer falls off the network. The only way i have found to get it to reconnect is to shut the printer down and restart it. I contacted support and they told me that there was no way to fix this "feature", sleeping can not even be turned off. They need to update the firmware, then maybe, you can use the wireless. The support staff was not knowledgeable at all. Every bad suggestion they had came after they put me on hold for 20 minutes to do research. I spent three hours on the phone and I got no where. I'd return it, but I need a printer and it does print well. -------Update 2015-08-26-------- Something the tech said in passing got me to thinking and I realized that my faithful Cisco Linksys wireless router was now 7 years old, at least.  So I decided to upgrade to a newer Asus, and now the printer wireless works reliably.  I would give it more stars, but I don't love it, it works okay. lower stars are for the customer service and the fact that the duplex-er does not seem to work reliably.

product_title: Brother MFCJ870 Wireless Color Inkjet All-In-One with Scanner, Copier and Fax Printer
review_headline: Delighted! Best little home-office printer I've ever purchased!
review_body: After exchanging an Epson WorkForce WF-2650 and getting a second one that had the same problems with spotty printing and constantly having to clean the printheads and waste ink, I decided to try this Brother. I've gone from purchasing the worst printer ever to pure delight. I don't have to print a few pages every day to keep it primed. In fact, I've gone a week between copies and it hasn't given me any problem so no more repeatedly cleaning heads and wasting ink to try to get one clear page. And when it has automatically cleaned the print heads itself, it doesn't take forever! The document feeder works great and is so handy when you have a bunch of pages to copy. The scan works just as it should though it took me a minute to figure out it's a 2-step process; you start the scan and when you get a visual of it on screen, you choose your options, like full page or cropping a section. I did have to install the scanner driver to get it to work correctly which is unusual for a Mac but no biggie. Entering the the wireless configuration was easy, and it has stayed pretty steady whereas I had to re-enter wireless info for the Epson every time I wanted to print and finally just connected with a USB cable. Love this wireless; I've had no trouble sending a printing job from my iPad in another room. Nice. I rarely am forced to fax anything these days but it will convenient to have that available when needed. Print quality is typical of an inkjet. It's not laser quality printing but it doesn't cost like a laser printer either. If you're a graphic designer and need high-quality color on upgraded stock, you should move up and spend more money. As far as the initial unpacking and setup of this Brother printer, I wish I had timed it! I've never had any setup go so smoothly and quickly. You have to unpack, install ink, install drivers on your computer and add paper and it pretty much takes care of everything else fairly quietly, fairly quickly. Maybe took about 15 minutes from when Iopened the box to first printed page. I think this printer is great for a home office. If you're looking for a printer to use every day, this is it. If you're looking for a printer to use only occasionally and still conserve ink (very important!), this is it. For a printer this cheap, just a little over $100, you can't beat this Brother.

product_title: SHARKK Portable Bluetooth 4.0 Mini Speaker 3.5 mm Aux Port Loud and Clear Sound with Bass. 8 Hour Playtime Has Built in Mic Speaker System Has Rechargeable Battery, Pause Play, Foward, Back Buttons. VERY EASY SET UP AND SIMPLE USE
review_headline: Okay for Minimal Requirements but Don't Count on all Functions to Work as Described
review_body: First, I need to qualify this review to indicate that I don't have a wide variety of other speakers to compare this to so some of the shortcomings may be very typical.  I simply don't know.  Purchased for use with an iPhone so I can listen to music at work.  My main problem was the extremely abbreviated instructions that come with this unit.  It's very possible that every difficulty I experienced is correctable but it's solution is not obvious.  The speaker paired up easily but none of the functions work as described in the one or two lines in the "manual".  The speaker also has a fair bit of high pitch humming when it is not connected or there is silence between the songs.  It works well and the sound quality is good as long as something is playing.  For such a small footprint, the bass response is impressive, which is what rates it a three with all of the other miscues I have had.  When I turned it on for the first time, it went through a series of colors but since has only illuminated in blue.  I also leave it in the off position and it works fine as long as the iPhone is connected directly to the speaker.  I tried everything I could think of and cannot get it to either play music via bluetooth connection or respond to volume controls as indicated on the scratch piece of paper that passes for a manual.

These cases are exposed to extreme high and low temperatures and all sorts of weather conditions.  I was getting labels printed before from a local company and they cost me almost twice as much as what I have calculated my cost to be with the LX900.  I also had to know what I needed a week before my gear left and now I can print them on the day it leaves if I have to.  I can also print directly from Photoshop which is nice because I don't have to export to PDFs anymore and take up more disk space.  I've even had clients come back and ask for more labels in order to label their own cases.  They look great, they withstand harsh conditions (using polyester and polypropylene labels), and the machine spits them out at a high rate of speed too.

product_title: Panasonic KX-TG9542B Dect 6.0 2-Line Cordless Phone System w/ Link-to-Cell & 2 TGA950B Handsets
review_headline: Great as a 2-line landline phone.  Link-to-cell-phone feature is weak. There is a 12-handset version of this phone.
review_body:
I recently purchased this 2-line phone w two extensions, as well as four additional extensions for use in our home. It has lots of nice features. The sound is clear and crisp. The handset is a great size and fits comfortably in the palm of your hand. It loads up phone book info from your mobile phone address book. It has a nice intercom feature. There are separate answering machines for the two lines. And I was particularly happy to take advantage of the call blocking features. My husband loves that he can set his handset not to ring between 11pm and 10am. (The setting is customized and only affects that one handset).

The bluetooth link to cellphone, however, is a disappointing feature that would have been fabulous, had it worked. My cell phone is always at the wrong end of the house, it seems, when calls come in. This was supposed to let me answer my cell phone from any handset in the house. I ended up disconnecting blue tooth and the cell phone feature after only a few days. Why? It does a TERRIBLE job of handling landline-to-cellphone calls, cellphone-to-landline calls and/or cellphone-to-cellphone calls. There is a lot of static and you can barely hear the person on the other end. I still like the phone overall, (as an upgrade to what I previously had) but it has a ways to go before it functions as an extension of your cell phone.

One other peculiarity to note: it was fairly easy to name all of the handsets. But the handset faces frequently default to VOICE MAIL 1 and VOICE MAIL 2. Took a bit of research to figure out how to clear that. The answer is to hold down the # button for 5 seconds and all of the phone faces will return to their proper screen. Don't know why we should have to keep doing that but at least the solution is simple.

A note of caution: this phone comes in two versions - one with a corded base and one with a cordless handset for the base. You can only add 6 handsets, so if you choose the latter,that means you can only add 5 more phones instead of 6. My previous phone system had a corded base so I was able to add 6 handsets giving me a total of 7 phones.

Update: Like several other reviewers, six handsets proved to be a frustration because we were used to having 8. I discovered that Panasonic makes a 12-handset version of this same phone (KX-TG9582B) which comes with 2 (or more handsets), so I purchased it directly from Panasonic @ $229. Now, we have an embarrassment of riches: 10 handsets and all is well. KX-TG9582B has all the same features as KX-TG9542B (and more). It uses the same handsets as the other model, so the initial investment was not totally wasted. If you need lots of handsets, go for this bigger two-line model. Note that the base is a corded phone, but a cordless base model may also be an option.

product_title: edding 751 Medium Bullet Tip Paintmarker Pack of of 2 - White
review_headline: Great for Drawing White Details on Balloons
review_body:
**This review is primarily for Balloon Artists**

The Edding 751 paint markers are fantastic for drawing white details on balloons. The ink goes on smoothly and dries very quickly - both things I need when doing line work. I use this marker primarily to put the white in eyes and to use as a base for other colors on dark colored balloons. For example, if you're looking to make the hourglass on black widow spiders, you can draw an hourglass, then use a Sharpie to go right over the white Edding color - the Sharpie color will sit right on top of the white and not blend in. I purchased these pens through Amazon via selling langton_distribution. The pens were shipped to me from the UK and arrived in less than 2 weeks (I received the pack in 12 days from date ordered). These pens last a really long time, and are the best white pen that I've ever used. It won't make your balloons pop, and doesn't smudge off after application. This pen is a pen that absolutely has to be in my bag.

The opening and closing operation are very smooth, and I do not get the sense that the pen was cheaply made as is suggested in some of the other reviews. The weight, feel, and grip are all great, and it looks great. However, it fails serve its primary purpose: it does not write! I have had it only a few days, and at first it was great. After signing a few documents it began to skip, and now it is hardly writing at all. In a way, it almost feels wrong to give the pen a bad review based on its bad ink refill, but as it is the original (and included) ink tube, I can't justify a higher star rating.

I'm going to have to buy a new refill and hope that fixes the problem.

product_title: CNMIP100 - Canon iP100 Mobile Inkjet Printer
review_headline: Outstanding device but it uses a lot of ink
review_body: This is an extraordinary little printer, ideal for someone who travels a lot but not great if you run a lot of copies,  as the ink cartridges do not last very long. It is lighter weight and physically smaller than the comparable HP device, and is a lot more reliable than the most recent version of the HP printer. The early version of the HP was a workhorse, but the newest version is not very good. This printer is a lot better.  I added the wireless link, which fits comfortably inside the side panel of the printer. A nice design feature, and so far it has worked  great.  I also added the external battery, which adds a little bulk but not much. The battery screws to the printer and therefore you need a screwdriver if you want to carry a second backup battery.  I have never used up the battery, though. It seems to have a pretty long life on each charge. It lasts a lot longer than the ink cartridges.  A nice feature is that when you run out of the  tricolor ink, the printer still will print with the black ink cartridge (the HP won't do that). Plus it warns you when ink is runming low. One caution;it can get b a little goofy when you open it to change the cartridge. Go slowly, and you may have to try a couple of times before you get the mechanism to move the  cartridges to the center, where they have to be to change them. Otherwise you may have to reboot the printer and your computer. I tend to rush and as a result I have had a problem once in a while.  Also be careful and feed the paper straight, as a crooked  feed can jam the printer, making  that double reboot necessary.  I wish you could get cartridges with more ink, as you could  with the HP. I  get about 200 copies legal size on one color cartridge. That is the only weakness. I  really like this printer and recommend it with that one caveat.

product_title: Texas Instruments TI BA II Plus Professional Financial Calculator - 10 Character(s) - LCD - Battery Powered IIBAPRO/CLM/4L1/A
review_headline: Positives Build quality seems fine. Negatives Stiff keys - this is very annoying ...
review_body:
I have to use this calculator in examination settings. I have a few problems with this model that may seem minor - but not really minor in a major test:

Positives
Build quality seems fine.

Negatives
Stiff keys - this is very annoying - even painful after a 3 hour test. Why so stiff?
Very difficult to read the secondary functions on the keyboard in most lighting. Why color them light gray?
The TI process to obtain answers seems overly cumbersome compared to HP models. The process is not intuitive.

Overall, I am seriously considering going back to an HP12c Platinum. There may be more bells and whistles on the TI, but for tests are they really needed? The HP can handle 98% of the calculations the TI can and is less of a pain to use. Outside of tests, a computer can run any calculation required.

product_title: 50 Old Aged Parchment 60lb Text Weight 8.5 X 11 inches Stationery Paper Colored Sheets Letter Size -Printable Old Parchment Semblance
review_headline: Not as great as it could be, but still pretty darn good.
review_body: When I first opened it, I was a little disappointed.  It literally looks like slightly colored computer paper, and doesn't look all that 'aged' to be perfectly honest.  I got the paper to fill my book of shadows, so it's necessary for my paper to hold up to a quill and ink.  The lack of thickness of this paper was concerning to me, but I gave it a shot anyway.  I didn't hold back, I pressed normally with my quill and loaded it up with a normal amount of ink just as if I were using it for more than a test run.  My quill tends to catch on most paper, but it wrote smoothly on this paper.  When I flipped the paper over to see how badly it bled, I was pleasantly surprised to see that it didn't bleed any more than a standard pen would on standard lined paper.  Yes, I can see that something was written on the other side of the page, but I cannot see what was written, nor do the impressions or ink from the front interfere with any writing I would do on the back of the page. It certainly isn't bad for the price and I will be buying it again, since I need a lot of paper for my project. But I am deducting a star because I will have to age this paper a little more, and it's not as thick as I thought it would be.  Overall though, it's worth purchasing again since it does hold up to what will be used on it (ie, my quill and ink).

My complaint is that the last 3 HP printers that I've bought (Officejet Pro 8620, Deskjet 3520 and this one) have an issue in that they \\"freeze\\" up if I leave them powered on and I have to unplug them and let them reboot before I can use them.  When I restart these printers by doing this, I get a message saying that this could damage the printer but I don't have a choice since I can't turn them off by using the power button.  HP solved this problem with a firmware update for the 3520 and it works okay now.  I've not been able to find a similar solution for the 8620 or this 4630.

product_title: Pilot Color Eno Neox Mechanical Pencil Lead, 0.7 mm, 8 Color Set (Japan Import)
review_headline: Pretty, but weak and not long-lasting
review_body:
I bought these lead to use when I was studying for my licensing exam. I color-coded the uses (green for definitions, blue for reference pages, purple for explanation of formula, etc.). Like another reviewer, it seems I might press down harder than I thought because the lead has a tendency to break easily. Though this is not a problem for me with regular lead, so it might be the related to the chemical makeup of the colored lead. I dealt with that by using them in mechanical pencils with a longer shaft at the tip, figuring the longer the sleeve/cylinder at the point of pressure, the more support it has and the less likely it will break. That helped a lot. I passed my exam with flying colors (ahem, pun not intended, ahem).

I decided to start using the lead at work, to help add some pep to my hand calculations and notes. They're great since they stand out from the drawings and I can highlight different assumptions based on colors. I'm one of those people who cringe at doing math with pen or marker, so the fact that I could write in multiple colors which can be erased easily seemed like a godsend. Then a few weeks later, I was looking through my notes to find some info I used to design something, and I couldn't find the page with all the blue writing. I looked again and found the sheet with the same drawing I wrote that info on, but the info was not there. When I looked harder, I saw that all of my writing had faded away! The ghost of my calculations and sketches left on the sheet looks like someone had erased the whole page. I went through my notepad to see other instances where I'd used the color pencils, and they were fading too. Yesterday, I looked through my main exam study book to show a coworker my color-coded system, and the writing is mostly still there, though has faded a bit on some pages. I hadn't opened the book in months. So perhaps the lead only fades over time when constantly exposed to air...? Maybe the quality that makes it so easy to erasealso allows it to fade so quickly. Who knows? All I know is that I won't be using this pretty lead for anything I need to write and save for reference for more than a few weeks.

product_title: RFID Blocking Sleeve - 8 Credit Card - Best Identity Theft Protection Made In USA With Tyvek And Aluminum - This RFID Sleeve Easily Fit in Your Wallet - Literally A Stronghold
review_body:
We've all seen it in the news, nowadays, high-tech thieves can hack and steal our identities in a snap. They could just passed you by at a mall, or a restaurant, pretty much anywhere and steal your information without you even knowing it. This is what we call, electronic pick-pocketing or crowd hacking and it's everywhere. They use an RFID scanner, same ones used in stores or restaurants when they scan your credit cards when you're paying. Any thief can purchase these types of scanner and can steal your identity from 3-feet away, without even touching you.

The RFID blocking sleeve is one of the best inexpensive ways to protect ourselves from thieves. It blocks the radio frequency that can scan your information. I love how my credit cards and IDs fit perfectly into the sleeves. The sleeves fit right in my wallets as well and I can still take them out easily. I also love that there's plenty of sleeves left for other family members to use. Without a doubt, the best way to protect ourselves from cyber thieves. It's a wonderful feeling, that peace of mind knowing that you're protected from e-pick-pocketing or crowd hacking.

This is a no-brainer, I definitely recommend this to family, friends, to anyone..

*I received this product at a reduced price in exchange for an honest and unbiased review.

review_headline: So very disappointed in this machine
review_body: So very disappointed in this machine. I bought in October and used a few times and loved it. No issues. I emailed their customer service because I thought (from the booklet it came with) that the feeding tray was missing, but that model apparently didn't have one. Ok, no problem, I will just make sure I guide it in. Well, I took it out to use today and it literally ate my laminating sheet. I wasn't laminating anything thick. And just like that, I lost what I was doing and my machine broke. What a piece of junk. I emailed Customer Service (the same email I used information@purplecows.net) and low and behold I get a rejected email back stating the email no longer exists. Purple Cow Customer Service, if you are out there, how do I reach you? Did they go out of business? So disappointed. If you are looking for a laminator, I wish I could recommend this one, but I would move on and try another brand. I am.

product_title: LD © Remanufactured Epson T6064 / T606400 High Yield (220ml) Yellow Ink Cartridge for 4800 Stylus Pro, 4800 Portrait Edition, 4880 Stylus Pro, 4880 ColorBurst Edition & 4880 Portrait Edition
review_headline: So the good news is they are inexpensive
review_body:
I got an email from Amazon marketplace to ask me to review this. I wouldn't have otherwise, since I'm fairly neutral about these ink cartridges.

So the good news is they are inexpensive. Compared to genuine epson ink, they are extremely cost effective. They also look relatively good. I'm not an ink expert, but I can't see an obvious difference between the results Epson's ink produces and this.

The bad news it they aren't terribly reliable with my printer. Ironically the one they are asking me to review (the yellow ink), is a replacement for one they shipped which the printer refused to read. That being said, it's entirely possible that there's some technique to get it to accept this cartridge in that scenario, and I just don't know it.

So yeah, I'll give it 4 stars. I'd say 10-20% of the cartridges I've purchased from LD haven't worked correctly, but given the fact that they are substantially cheaper than Epson, it's still worthwhile.

product_title: HIGHROCK widely Infrared Remote Control Receiver + Emitter + USB Adaptor for IR Extender Repeater
review_headline: Nothing special but does the job.
review_body:
My only complaint is that the length of cable between the IR receiver and the transmitter could be longer.

The set up is pretty simple.
1. Plug unit into either the included USB wall plug or a powered USB port on any nearby device (many cable boxes, smart tvs etc have usb ports now)
2. Position the larger node (IR receiver (part that's lit up)) somewhere your remote can transmit clearly to it.
3. Place the smaller node (IR transmitter) where it has clear line of sight to the devices you wish to control.
4. Profit

The only issue I had setting it up is that the media cabinet I was placing the transmitter node in was fairly tight so I had to make sure it was more or less directly in front of the IR "eye" on my A/V receiver.

review_body: This pen has a very nice weight to it, so that I don't have to press down on the paper like regular pens. The magnets are very strong and hold together very well when you write. The best way to handle it is to grip it gently. If you grip it too tightly, the magnets shift just a little. The magnets force me to hold my pen in a way that is much more comfortable to write. If you're the type of person that grips your pens tightly, you'll have to loosen up when you use this. I know some reviewers have had issues with their ink. I'm not sure why. I've been using the magnetic pen for a few days now and have not had a single issue. It writes consistently, with a nice smooth flow. I haven't tried any of the tricks that are seen on the Polar website. Just played around with it very simply. I love that the pen comes with two different styluses and all these ball bearings to help build neat sculptures out of your pen. It's quite fun all in all.

product_title: Apollo Mesh Back Drafting Stool
review_headline: Garbage - Do Not Buy This chair really seemed promising
review_body:
Garbage - Do Not Buy
This chair really seemed promising. The seller shipped it fast and all indications were good.

Then the chair arrived. From the box, it looked like a little suspicious. You know how most manutfactuers make a long list of benefits about their product on the box? Yeah, well this has 4 of them. All of which every chair has.

After assembling the chair, I learned the following:
It has a "ratcheting back rest" - well, this doesn't work at all. You set the height you want and back rest just falls right down. There is no way to adjust the tension on the ratchet at all. It's flimsy and crappy, it doesn't work at all unless you want the back in the lowest position and you're really short.

There is no way to adjust the seat position. It's canted at a weird angle and not comfortable. There is no way to adjust this so you're stuck with the manufacturers setting. It's welded to the metal support so there is no way to change it.

The foot ring diameter is way to small to make sense. When sitting on the chair your knees are bent all the way back to reach the foot ring. Completely uncomfortable and poorly designed. If you look closely at the image for this product you'll see what I mean.

The arm rest adjust maybe 3.5 inches tops which I guess is fine but there is no tension on them. So they rattle left to right any time the chair moves. These, unlike the back rest, do manage to stay in the set position.

This chair got good reviews because it fits a smaller person. I am 6'-2" and the chair doesn't fit at all. Don't buy it if you're less than 5'-6".
I'm ordering a new one and returning this asap.

product_title: Epson WorkForce Pro WF-5690 Inkjet Multifunction Printer - Color - Plain Paper Print - Desktop C11CD14201
review_body:
Bought this model based on a Consumer Reports review. The first unit we received printed white lines through photos and graphics and the output was grainy. Called Epson tech support. Worked with them until they determined the unit was faulty and sent me a new one. The second one was actually worse than the first. It smeared ink on both our office letterhead and Epson photo paper. And photos and graphics were still grainy. We have a color laserjet that's 600x600 dpi that produces better output than this printer, which is supposed to have twice that resolution. The WorkForce Pro WF-5690 was basically a big waste of money.

I will say that, unlike other reviewers, I found Epson tech support to be quite helpful. I've never had a manufacturer send out a replacement w/o having to fight about it before.

product_title: Epson Expression Premium XP-620 Wireless Color Photo Printer with Scanner and Copier
review_body:
When my XP-600 works, and when I am satisfying its insatiable appetite for ink, it works quite well. But two things a potential buyer should know. First, I returned the printer to Epson four times during the first six months. The screen would tell me that the ink cartridges I was using were not compatible with the printer, even though they were the Epson cartridges that came with the printer. Of course, if even one of the five cartridges does not work, the printer shuts down. The fourth exchange time appeared to be the charm as I still have the printer, but .....

Even though nearly all of my printing is in black and white, hardly a week goes by without the screen warning me that one of the color cartridges is running low on ink. Before long, the machine shuts down until I replace the color cartridge. Mind you, nearly all of my printing is in black and white.
I would guess that after two years, I have spent twice as much on ink cartridges than I paid for the printer.... and I do not really print very much. Beware.

product_title: Five Star Advance Student Weekly / Monthly Planner
review_body: Recently, I got a very pretty planner that I find myself not wanting to use, because it just seems too pretty for everyday appointments and such.  This one, however, I have no reservations about using, since it looks like an everyday planner--nothing special, but totally useful.  There's lots of room for day-to-day notes, as well as monthly calendars.  There's also all sorts of extra stuff in the back, like a map of the United States; a map of the world; conversion charts; including a liquid measurement one I wish I had last week; spelling tips; proofreading symbols; the dates of all the holidays you would ever need to know for three years; etc.  I'm actually surprised and happy there are still products like this; since people today tend to use computers and cell phones to keep track of their schedules, and find out any information they need.  It makes me hopeful we won't all one day be swallowed up by computers and cell phones.

product_title: Canon PIXMA MG3522 Wireless Inkjet Photo All-in-One Printer - Print, Copy, Scan
review_body:
I bought this unit primarily to print some photos but, needed a printer that would do other office chores as well. How well it works? It is a good, if slow, clunky and noisy photo printer. It is worse at other chores. It prints, well..., eventually. There is so much clumsy, unwanted extra, truly useless software, which this dumps into your computer, and is immensely clumsy to use. The photo I submitted shows just a few, very few, of the options, functions, or what all that it comes with. In the process, it makes just trying to align the printer after changing the cartridges (granted I am not real computer savvy BUT, I haven't had this problem on any printer we have owned previously!) can take me up to an hour of searching trying to just find the commands to do that.
Then, when you go to print, you hit the button and wait a minute or two (I mean literally) then it clanks, buzzes and whirrs (this is in "quiet" mode mind you) and then, ifinally, starts to print. When it puts out your page there is a long delay, eventually followed by more clanking, whirring and buzzing then it finally stops. THEN, if you've a mind, you can print something else.
This thing is worse than useless. It makes doing a job harder.

product_title: Olympus VN-702PC Voice Recorder
review_body:
I used this for ethnographic field work for ten months in a tropical environment and it didn't fail even once. It also has a nifty stand, that allows you to prop it at an angle towards a speaker, when you set it on a table. Also, it comes with a nice cover, which protects it. I bought a sony voice recorder and that one honestly didn't have these perks.

Also, this one says that it accepts a normal micro SD card and it accepts a normal micro SD card. The sony tape recorder, on the body of it, said it needed an M2 micro SD card. I went to my research country after buying those cards, and guess what, they didn't work in the tape recorder - I had to share my normal micro SD card between this Olympus voice recorder and the Sony one. So, honestly Olympus is doing something right.

product_title: HP ENVY COLOR PRINTER
review_headline: We had to buy a Service Contract
review_body:
We've purchased our last HP printer from HP. I have a HP Diskjet 960. My wife had a HP C4150, printer, scanner, copier and decide to get a HP Wireless ENVY 5530. When the ENVY 5530 arrived we followed instructions and removed the C4150 and tried to install the ENVY 5530. It wouldn't install.

We called the 800 number and got someone in New Deli speaking semi-English. They told us the ENVY 5530 would not install until we purchased a $200 iYogi Service Plan to make her computer accept the wireless ENVY 5530 printer. I told them our C4150 worked just fine and we could use its cable. They told me that wouldn't work; that we have to buy the Service Plan.

When I told them I would return the ENVY 5530 to HP, they said they'd sell us the Service Plan for $99.98 and that was the only way. I felt trapped and purchased the Service Plan in order to have a printer. After the purchase, they told me to go ahead and use the old cable, and it would work.

I don't know if this is bate a switch or HP's way of making a few more bucks, but I'll never purchase another HP printer.

product_title: 3M Commercial Office Supply Div. Products - Tear-By-Hand Packaging Tape, 1-7/8"x52', 1-1/2" Core, Clear - Sold as 1 RL - Packaging tape is ideal for mailing, moving, and package sealing. No scissors or dispensers are required. Tape tears straight by hand, but is amazingly durable. Adhesive is made of an aggressive hot melt rubber resin. Packaging tape meets U.S. Postal Service and UPS regulations.
review_headline: Love the ease of use of this tear-by-hand tape! Great product.
review_body: Love the tear-by-hand tape but can't find it at my local Staples (small town with only one office supply store). So, I order from Amazon. Fabulous stuff. Thick enough to secure boxes for shipping and it's so easy to use without having to mess with scissors, or worse - that plastic holder thingie that's necessary with other rolls of tape. I wouldn't even buy another kind of packing tape if I had a heavy-duty metal holder, like they use at the UPS store. That thing would take up so much space! By the way, each roll has 52' of tape (that's 629"), so I'm not sure what some other reviewers have complained about. And it's almost 2" wide, like other packing tapes. Another thing that I like about this tape is that it doesn't have the toxic smell of other packing tapes. This tape is a great product. It's the only packing tape I buy, now that I know how easy it is to use.

product_title: T10 Single Line Phone W/ Convertible Headset 45159-11
review_headline: The phone is great for my needs
review_body: The phone is great for my needs. I work a ministry for about three hours every night. Holding a regular phone to my ear for three hours doesn't work well at all as it makes my arm ache. This phone comes with volume and tone controls on the side. The metal bar used to hang the headset isn't needed and doesn't work that well, in my opinion, as it won't hang the headset as shown in the photo, so I discarded it and just lay the headset on top of the phone. I also had the T20 dual line phone, in the past, because I had two phone lines. The dual line phone is heavier and uses a power supply which is included. The T10 uses phone company power. Just plug it into your phone line and it's good to go. Incidentally, if you ever find it's stopped working, it's most likely the headset cord. I accidentally pulled mine a bit hard. New headsets can be bought separately, so don't assume the phone has quit.

review_headline: I was looking for a multi-function printer to work with ...
review_body: I was looking for a multi-function printer to work with Linux/Ubuntu.  I installed this printer in Ubuntu 14.04 LTS. I t took several days due to some simple issues. First get and use the latest version of HPlip. The included version in 14.04 did not work. Second, check the date and time on the LCD display. Mine was 03/31/00. I had to change it through the LCD display menu to make anything print. Third, make sure you have set the printer activation correctly using the LCD. Since my printer is connected via ethernet, I used network activation for my parameter. Other choices included USB or web. If it was not for these 'hidden' config issues I would rate it a 5 star.

product_title: Noodlers Ahab Fountain Pen December 25Th
review_headline: A quality flex writer, pretty cheap!
review_body: This pen is such a great value! It fills smoothly, starts right away, and doesn't dry out if left open for a cup of coffee.  Surprisingly smooth with just a hint of useful feedback on rough paper.  And even that almost disappears with a lubricated ink (e.g. N's Black Eel). It makes a moderately wet line so you can see good color with your ink and gives OK shading with inks that can do that. It is not a wet noodle and it takes a little pressure to get the tines to spread, but with minimal practice you can get good line variation even with normal writing.  The secret of really pretty flex writing is in the thin lines. I'm still working on getting a good quick-stroke fine line from the Ahab, but I believe it's possible. Ink flow can definitely keep up, so if you get railroading, change ink or go slower. This is a large fat pen.  It is light even when posted, but expect it to fill your hand.  I like that.  I gave it five stars because if you like a thinner pen, it's not Noodler's fault. Not a calligraphy flex pen, but a go-to daily writer that can flex.

product_title: Multifunctional Voice Recorder Portable Rechargeable Digital Audio Dictaphone MP3 Player (8GB)
review_body:
[I was sent this product for review.]

I could bore everyone with stories of Ye Olden Days, when as a cub reporter I felt I'd hit the big time with my Lanier hand recorder. It was so small....for the time. No download capability, though; you had to hand-transcribe those little micro-cassettes. I have a bag of them somewhere....They weren't cheap!

This little gizmo is an order of magnitude more useful. Small enough to carry in my purse -- or my pocket when hiking — and have a great idea for a new blog post, lecture topic, or household task I've been forgetting about.

I love that I can download the sound files and organize them.

Is the quality top notch? No. Do I expect it to be? No.

review_headline: Great product but does not work on an iPad with the Doxie app
review_body: This is a terrific  product. The quality of the scans is very good and it is extremely portable.  The one drawback is that it does not work on an iPad or iPhone with the Doxie app, and I have not yet found a way to compile pages into a single document.  The scans are saved as JPEG's, which can be converted to PDF's on an iPad or computer, but that doesn't mean you can compile them into a single pdf document.  There may be an app to do that, but I haven't yet found it. Apparently, the app only works with the wireless Doxie scanner, which is more than double the price. If I am wrong, please someone tell me.  Also, I do not recommend the case for the Doxie One, as there is no place to put the charger in it. So in less you want to carry the scanner in a case and the charger separately, I would just recommend finding another way to transport it.

product_title: Sony ICDTX50 Digital Flash Voice Recorder
review_body: This recorder is the best I've ever used, and I used many. It's a pleasure to use for its simplicity and excellent sound quality for voice (haven't tried for music). In mono high quality voice mode it provides 184 hours with the built in memory and this can be increased many folds with a micro-SD card. review_headline: Disappointed... it loses connection and turns off by itself.
review_body: I had no luck with this projector despite the good reviews. I tried playing a movie via HDMI, but about one fourth into the movie the projector started to lose connection and the main screen appeared. This happened about four times, then the projector started to turn off by itself. It started to turn off half way through the movie and after the third or fourth time I gave up and put it back in the box and sent it back for a refund. It looks like it could be a good little projector, since it projects a rich image and it can be expanded to about 50 inches. Also there are many ways in which you can get it to project what you want, for example you can use the RCA's (I think that's what they're called), Mini SD card, and even HDMI, but unfortunately it could not even go for half ann hour without malfunctioning.

product_title: AAXA LED Android Pico/Micro Projector with LED
review_headline: Wonky. Streaming apps not working. No bluetooth over HDMI. Umpa Lumpa orange skin tones.
review_body: Good start but this product, and I suspect most other Android projectors, shouldn't have been brought to market quite yet. I couldn't get one single streaming app from Playstore to work properly; HBO GO, Discovery Channel, History Channel, Netflix all crashed, buffered eternally or reverted back to the "Play" screen. With Intel Compute and Google Chromebit options coming out spring 2015, better choice is to go with standard projector that meets your needs and add-on the IS via HDMI.  Try as I might, getting rid of the hideous orange skin tones became an exercise in futility. By the time you get the skin tones close, the overall hue of the picture is greenish-blue. There is no way to color balance this system.  One of my main reasons for choosing this Android projector over the others is the built-in bluetooth. Unfortunately, I discovered that using a media source over HDMI (chromecast, roku, fire stick, etc) leaves you with only the options of using projector's useless speakers or the 3.5mm audio out jack. AAXA confirmed it is presently a limitation with no solution near term.  You will never find yourself boosting the lumens on this projector because 1) it turns off after set time, which is shorter than your standard movie 2) the fan noise is unbearable in that setting.  I ended up purchasing the LG PA77U Smart Projector refurbished for $499 shipped. Came with a 1 yr warranty from LG. It's amazing what you get for that price. 3D Ready with 2D to 3D conversion built-in, 700 Lumens, Digital HDTV Tuner and Antenna, the awesome Magic Remote in addition to standard remote that blows the card remotes you get with AAXA projectors out of the water. Another nice feature is an A/V sync to adjust for the lag you typically get with bluetooth audio streaming via 3.5mm adapter. Another bonus, the fan is imminently more quite than the AAXA.  Bottom line is I cannot recommend this projector and I would urge you to look into non-Android smart projector till someone implements it right. My opinion is these projectors have a split personality, with two separate heads (Android and native OSD) that do not integrate well.

That said, my hands were to sensitive for the sand paper esque feel of the grip on this pencil. And being a programmer who writes her test code by hand, I erase A LOT, and this eraser has got to be the worst I have ever seen on a high end pencil. It does not stay in place, and you have to either use it as a clicker, or an eraser; you can't have it both ways with this pencil. I'm moving to a Faber Castel and giving this one to my secretary.

product_title: eLink Pro® Chair Mount Ergonomic Keyboard / Laptop Tray System Plus Chair Mount Armrest/Mouse Tray _ Walnut
review_headline: If only it were meant for a decent chair
review_body: I bought this to install on a DX Racer King Zero Series chair.  The most immediate problem is that the cross-extender (that immediate tube that goes from your chair stem and takes a 90 degree bend up) has two unequal lengths to it, with the shorter going up.  On a chair with a significant seating platform (rocking, reclining, locking into a full reclined position, tensioner, etc.), plus steel tube frame and decent padding, the platform at its highest extent barely clears the highest part of the seat base cushion by 2".  My thighs are >2" in diameter.  That is a NO GO situation.  Assembly directions are via pictogram and saying which letter parts are used.  Pictorgram 2does not identify the chair stem, period.  Pictogram 3 misidentifies part 'l' as part 'i' (part 'i' is a screw and nut, while part 'l' is a plastic washer).  All parts are clearly labeled and they even sent another part 'i' along, which is good considering those are the first to be likely to strip out.  Assembly took about 45 minutes for one person in a dimly lit room with much cussing trying to get the nuts on to the cross-attachment piece and then headscratching on just how a nut and bolt were supposed to work where the pictorgram did not identify they at all.  Disassmbly went much faster.  A quick placing of the cross-piece against my prior chair (also with controls and such on the bottom, although it was a cheap adjustable chair from years back) gives an apparent 2" of clearance over the worn seat.  Still not enough for my thighs.  For a standard office seat with relatively thin padding and no sophisticated controls giving elevation to the seat base, I can see where this system would work for me.  The separate mouse platform does me no good without the tray, as this is a system level replacement for another keyboard/mouse platform I'm using on my desk.  If one does not work, the other is mooted.  PROs - Relatively easy to put together - Well labeled attachment parts, though packagedin a single bag - It would fit my extended size keyboard  CONs - Tray does not clear seat by very much - Poor pictogram labeling - Functional for the right chair and person  Am I sending it back?  No.  Why?  The problematic piece can be replaced by 3/4  x 36 (or 3/4 x 48 if I have any future plans for more attachments, the OD being nominal 1" so 3/4" Schedule 40 pipe) pipe with a 90" bend in it (or simple elbow fitting).  Drill a few holes in it and then the problem is fixed.  Cosmetically it won't look great, true.  What I get in return is an extra 4-6" of elevation.  Yes this will have to be done by hand because I will not have an equal out and up, but more up than out.  Sadly just using the piece sent won't do it as it does need a good 16" out to clear the seat and arm necessary for mouse use by this system.  Plus something a bit better in the screw and nut realm, as the ones sent aren't what I would call 'heavy duty'.

product_title: HP Deskjet 1512 Inkjet All-in-One Printer
review_headline: Doesn't have driver support for windows 8.1 and 10.0
review_body:
This is the worst printer I've ever tried to set-up. It has very minimal wordless airy sketches of installing. The installation disc does not self start, and after manually starting it was virtually un-readable by my pricey new Lenovo Core I5's DVD/supplemental drive/CD-writer. Probably damaged disc, but why they use big disc instead of more tech recent flash drive USB set up programs I have no idea. HP Tech Support was useless. Apparently their windows drivers for 8.1 and 10.0, which are my only platforms, either . HP tech support did not recognize the printer as their product. It's a cheap plastic thing and the HP supplied ink cartridges have to be FIRMLY pressed in place, which they don't tell you. I even brought their cable ( doesn't come with printer). This is a bad product in many ways, including although Amazon agreed to accept the return, they send to a return label for UPS which you have to print!! Hello?? Yes they do have a link so you can send it to a friend to print, but seem to assume that friend is within walking distance!! That day UPS came for the package, and the every next 2 days.So I see my friend this weekend, pick up the labels and have to drive to a UPS support center myself and deal with the abrupt staff there.
In sum, it is not a printer, just a CHEAP quick sale item, unless you are still operating on windows VISTA or 7.0. You get what you pay for, and I kick myself on this one, too.

product_title: Pilot Prera Iro-Ai Calligraphy-Nib Transparent Body Fountain Pen
review_body:
This is pen lays down the finest line of any fountain pen I've ever used, even though it is only a fine nib. It writes almost like a technical pen. I have tried EF fountain pens in the past only to be disappointed by poor ink flow. Not so with the Prera. Noodler's Bulletproof Black, Ottoman Azure and Namiki blue all flow smoothly out of this pen. The nib also has a little bit of flex to it so pressure gets you a slightly darker line. It writes very well on cheap paper - no bleeding.
It is short, but posted it is very comfortable in my average sized hands. The build quality for a relatively inexpensive pen is great.
My opinion is this pen makes a great all-purpose, use at the office fountain pen for the extra-fine pen lover. If you like thicker lines, maybe the medium is what you're looking for.

The new cartridge arrived but it leaked a tremendous amount of ink during shipping so I had a mess to clean up before I tried to put the cartridge in the printer. See pics.

When I received this second cartridge it was the correct shape as the original cartridge that came in my printer but it was cheaply constructed and did not fit well into the printer at all. After trying to install the cartridge, in and out several times, it would never be recognized correctly in my printer. See pics.

For the price and the experiment level, fantastic purchase.

review_body:
Great little projector. Can't go wrong for the price. Projects 50 inches no problem on the side of a white house when it's dark out.

You need external speakers. No questions asked. If you think your phone has bad speakers built in, this thing is 100X worse. Uses a regular aux cable.

We use it to play Super Smash Bros and Mario Cart on summer nights out in the yard. I take it from my house to a friend's with ease since it's so small depending on where we will hang out that day. Simply run an extension cord and a surge protector/power strip to power the game console, external speakers, and the projector and we play video games or a movie depending on the mood. We used this thing for almost 6 hours strait until 4 AM on independence day earlier this month without a problem.

Highly recommended.

I am going to use these journals to write to my baby in - I think the "Love where you're going" quote on the front is appropriate for this usage.

I feel like a journal like this would be $12-20 in the store and I got it for under $7.

product_title: iGearPro 16GB USB Flash Drive Digital Audio Voice Recorder - Rechargeable Mini Hidden Pen Drive - 1 Year Warranty
review_body:
This small,simple, unobstrusive little gadget is a nice little addition to the arsenal of the audial voyeur, Star Trek afficianado looking to keep a Captain's log, or anybody who needs to make an audio file. Sixteen gigs is a lot of gigs for something like this, so it doubles nicely as a general use flash drive. You can find cheaper flash drives, but if you're looking for a multi-use portable recorder, this may be your stop.

It's about the size of a man's thumb, typical of a flash drive so portability isn't an issue. The main issues are that it needs to be kept charged by regularly plugging it into a USB port, there's no speaker so you can't play back your recordings until you get to a computer, and it takes almost 30 seconds to begin recording whe you switch it on, which is weird, In addition to that, the recorder picks up a lot of extraneous noise in your pocket, probably from scraping against the fabric.

While the description claims the range is ten feet, it's really more a matter of volume. Low voices won't be picked up well unless the mic is right by the source, but as long as the voice s loud and clear, it will be understandable even beyond the stated range. It's simple to use too. Just flip the switch to "on", wait until the light turns blue, record, flip the switch to "off", plug it into a computer's USB drive, find the VOICE folder, and listen to what you've got. You won't be recording you hit debut single on it, but it should get the job done for interviews and whatnot so long as the voice being recorded is loud. A good buy for anyone whose projects require recording on the go.

product_title: Brother HL-L2340DW Compact Laser Printer, Monochrome, Wireless, Duplex Printing, Amazon Dash Replenishment Enabled
review_body:
I have had very good success with Brother printers in the past, but not so much with this one. I had originally ordered this model from Amazon but returned it for replacement (same model) due to constant wireless connection problems. I should say that I have a lot of network (wireless and otherwise) and systems expertise. I don't know everything but I'm pretty good when it comes to troubleshooting and isolating the point of failure. The replacement printer worked fine for awhile, but then it would start to fail to be "available" as either an AirPrint or Bonjour printer (Macintosh and iPad/iPhone users will know what I'm talking about). Only a reset would bring it back to life, and then only for about an hour. I have gone through many troubleshooting steps and am able to rule out other factors, which in these complex systems could have been the source, but are not in this case. The upshot is that while I am still in the process of escalating the problem with Brother support, so far the problem is not resolved and Brother support seems very reluctant to believe that the printer could be the problem.

The sole reason that I bought this printer was for its AirPrint support so that I would have something that iOS devices could print to. If that protocol is not reliable on this printer, then it is useless for my purposes. I'll post results of my tech support effort but so far my positive experiences with Brother have been heavily damaged by both the ongoing difficulties with this printer and with Brother's lousy customer service attitude.
===================
UPDATE APRIL 20 2015
===================
A Brother support engineer called me back regarding the Bonjour and AirPrint problems. He acknowledged that he had been able to reproduce the problem in his lab and that other users were reporting the same problem with this printer series. The problem seems to be with the v1.07 firmware. I started experiencing the problem after I installed the v1.07 firmware (v1.06 seemed to be stable with respect to AirPrint and Bonjour). The support engineer told me that I should expect a new version of the firmware to be released, but no time frame given, that should correct the problem. For the time being, buyers should be aware of protocol issues with the current firmware release (which may be shipped with your printer if you purchase it now) and Bonjour and AirPrint may have the same problems as with my printer. If your printer has the v1.07 firmware it is, unfortunately, not possible to downgrade to the v1.06 firmware, according to this software engineer.

I will post additional information if/when Brother releases new firmware.ed to be stable with respect to AirPrint and Bonjour). The support engineer told me that I should expect a new version of the firmware to be released, but no time frame given, that should correct the problem. For the time being, buyers should be aware of protocol issues with the current firmware release (which may be shipped with your printer if you purchase it now) and Bonjour and AirPrint may have the same problems as with my printer. If your printer has the v1.07 firmware it is, unfortunately, not possible to downgrade to the v1.06 firmware, according to this software engineer. I will post additional information if/when Brother releases new firmware.

product_title: Swingline ClassicCut Guillotine Paper Trimmer
review_headline: Card stock? Good luck.. it's like cutting a steak with a butter knife.
review_body:
I didn't test this on thinner paper, but I used this on a glossy card stock. Not sure of the weight off the top of my head, but it wasn't really that thick or heavy. Basically, first cut out of the box gave me jagged cuts comparable to tearing it with your hands. Not acceptable at all. Mind you, I was doing this with one sheet at a time. if it were 5-10 at once I could see it having difficulty. This is a heavy duty version of the Swingline "Lite" cutter that I have and have been using for a while, yet it cuts worse.

The base & overall construction of this item feels very steady & stable compared to the LITE model--I was impressed. but there was something off with the blade, it seems. I'll stick to the LITE model, for $40 less. Only reason I was buying a new cutter is I used my LITE cutter so much that the blade dulled.

If you're using lighter paper, maybe you'll have better luck. But in my opinion there's no excuse for a lesser model performing better than the heavy duty / more expensive variant. Submitted return request immediately--what a shame.

product_title: rOtring Rapid PRO Mechanical Pencil
review_headline: Excellent pencil, with only one slight flaw (that may not bother most people)
review_body: This is an excellent pencil. The look, size, make, and feel of it is fantastic. It is on the heavy side, so if you're a fan of light weight drawing utensils, this may not be for you. However, I happen to love the weight of it, and you couldn't ask for a better design. Everything is heavy-duty and solid, so you don't have to worry about it breaking. It is designed so precisely that nothing wiggles around, which is an issue that I have found in most other mechanical and clutch pencils.    The only complaint I have (which isn't a major one) is that the built in pencil sharpener doesn't seem to sharpen the lead to a very good point, but instead leaves it somewhat dull, about as sharp as a .9 or .7mm mechanical pencil lead. This isn't huge, and perhaps it's due to user error, but since I use it a lot for drawing, and I prefer the option to have a sharp point, it bugs me a bit. However this flaw wasn't substantial enough to reduce my 5 star rating. This is the best drawing/writing utensil I have ever held.

product_title: Smead Viewables Quick Fold Tabs, 45 per Pack (64912)
review_headline: NOT and improvement over the original.
review_body: I have been using Smead Viewables labels for 11 years and I was really disappointed in this new variation.  If you are unfamiliar with the original product, it required you to print a label, affix it to the plastic tab and then cover it with a clear plastic protective sheet.  It can be pretty time consuming and I've always felt guilty about the waste when you no longer need the tab.  I've tried to re-use them but you have to take off the old label because new labels won't stick to the old ones.  When I saw these, I thought I could print directly to the tab and skip the sticking.  I foolishly also thought they were made of card stock.  Wrong!  You get a sheet of  plastic pre-scored tabs that you cannot print on.  You have to use the enclosed sheets of labels then peel and stick just like before.  You don't have to add the clear protector but you still have to punch out the tabs from the sheet and fold them.  So, no fewer steps.  Unfortunately, there is no cost benefit, either.  The price for 45 of these Quick Fold Tabs is $13.75  or $.31 per label.  A 160-pack refill pack can be purchased on Amazon for $9.58 or $.06 per label.  Epic fail, Smead!!! I'll stick with the original product.

product_title: Premium Nylon Apple Watch Band by Monowear (Series 1 & 2)
review_body: I would have loved to have given this band more stars but it fell a little short in my opinion. First let me say this company looks to be the first and only legit 3rd party band provider out there, so i doubt you'll find anything better. The pro's are the adapter is included (which is a must for me) so they slide on and off your watch face with little effort so swamping bands is a piece of cake. The quality is actually decently good too. The cons however, I think are the price point is a little steep for the material, but the fact that is has the adapter already on it, maybe it adds a little to the price, but I would expect something of this material (nylon) with an adapter to be priced around $40 rather than $60, BUT they are the first out there so they get to charge whatever they want and I and others will be willing to fork it over (can't blame them I guess). The MAJOR downfall is the size of the band - I think is way too short. Just because I own the 38mm watch doesn't mean I have tiny wrists. I just wanted the small watch face. The band barely fits me on the last hole and leaves no overlap to pass through the slots on the other side, which is kind of a bummer because a bit of chunkiness in my band is the style i was going for. I think there should be a large and small size option regardless of the size watch you own.

product_title: Easy-Step Door Stops
review_headline: It Doesn't Get Easier than This!
review_body:
[[VIDEOID:e259a4a680a61fc5d4a6af7c12287d16]] I installed an automatic door closer on our laundry room door to keep my dogs away from a litterbox. While it's been great for restricting their movement, it's restricted mine as well and made it a pain to move around with a full laundry basket in my arms. This easy-stop door stop is the perfect solution to help me get in and out as I need to!

I've lost my fair share of plastic and wooden wedge-shaped door stops, and had given up on using them. This door closer attaches to the door easily with just three screws which makes it impossible to lose! I love that I don't have to search around just to keep my door open or have to worry about wedging a piece of plastic underneath the door!

Because I'm worried about my laundry room door, having a hands-free door closer that I don't have to struggle with is a must. This door closer flips down with just a slight press from my toe without me having to juggle around a full laundry basket to see what I'm doing. After adjusting the rubber foot just once this stop has held the door consistently, even on our uneven concrete floor. product_title: Safco Products STOW AWAY Dolly, Black, 4045BL
review_headline: Versatile Dolly for Moving Groceries, Shipping Boxes, Storage Tubs
review_body:
This SAFCO PRODUCTS STOW AWAY DOLLY is one of the best purchases I've ever made on Amazon. I have a bad back, so I use it for transporting moderately heavy grocery and hardware store purchases (e.g., cases of bottled water, bags of mulch or potting soil) from my car to my house. I also use it to move indoors the large boxes that FedEx, UPS, and USPS deliver to my front door. And I use it to shift loaded 14-gal. and 18-gal. [[ASIN:B0014CVDA4 Rubbermaid Roughneck]] tubs around my house and garage.

A feature I find particularly useful is the bright yellow, heavy-duty, nylon pull rope. It makes it possible to move boxes (carefully) without strapping them down. It's a bit tricky to control the loaded dolly with just the rope, but you learn quickly enough. A word of caution: the pull rope can be a trip hazard, if you don't pay attention to where you drop it--I learned the hard way!

The dolly is lightweight, and very easy to carry with the built-in handle. It stores standing upright on one end, and takes up little garage space. The 220-lb. capacity is more than adequate for me, because I try to keep shipping boxes and local store purchases under 50 lbs. total weight.

product_title: CPR V202 Call Blocker - Block All Robocalls, Political Calls, Scam Calls, Telemarketing Calls, Unwanted Calls On Landline Phones. Block All Nuisance Calls At The Touch Of A Button Using Caller Id
review_body:
We bought the v202 version over concerns about compatibility with US phones. I'm happy to report that it works fine with our cordless phones. The CPR unit is placed in series. I can block calls from my handset with #2. And I can program other numbers with **7#. I blocked everything: international, out-of-area, private-caller. You can block any prefix; not just all 10 digits. I block "0" (scammers), "1" (international area codes), various US area codes, various US area code + extensions, as well as 10-digit numbers.

Block your own number if they pretend to be you.

We had been keeping track of all the junk calls. So, we had a list. We entered about 40 numbers into the call blocker first day. There are supposed to be 200 built in as well. But, I dont know how to list them. The capacity is 1200. Should be enough for awhile.

We knew which ones used the same area code + extension, but varied the last 4 digits. With this system, you can block those fools too.

My phone went from 3-4 junk calls per day to blessed silence.

We got surprised one day when the phone rang. Turned out to be the dentist office verifying an appointment.

My last two printers were both Samsung - I was looking for a basic home color printer. Simply put those printers suck, do not buy. I threw the first out after a year as it broke. The second broke after 2 years. Customer service is horrible. Ohter things that are no good with the samsung: it prints slow, wireless is really hard to hook up (for some reason).

The Brother here was easy to hook up to wireless. Really I highly recommend for home printer use it's worth the extra $100.

product_title: HP ENVY COLOR PRINTER
review_headline: HP gets a big Razzberry for this Jam.
review_body: Just 14 months after purchasing an HP Envy 5530, the printer gives a consistent error message after powering up. It says the print carriage is jammed. It gives this message after running the print head carriage all the way left, then back to the right. There is no jam, paper, debri, sticky residue, errant sponge, or any other jam in or near the print head carriage. It simply gives the message on power up. This is a failure of what was a nice printer. At 14 months, and just 2 months out of warranty, this printer is now worth a one star rating. The printer has had 4 sets of ink cartridges in the past 14 months it was working. It was kept sealed in a storage tote inbetween the times it was used. The printer is clean, little used, but completely useless. It worked fine the day before, was put away clean, but powered up with a fault. HP gets a big Razzberry for this Jammed Message.

product_title: Ivation Multipurpose Gooseneck 7-LED Dimmable Clip Light with Stand
review_headline: This is a very handy item to have, especially for households with kids or those of use needing glasses.
review_body:
// CRYSTAL CLEAR
The magnification is very clear and sharp. Everything from edge to edge is in super sharp detail. NO fading or warping of the magnification near the edges of the lens.

// LIGHT
The light is very bright and helpful. Great for bright rooms as well as dark situations. If you are thinking of using this to read, know that the light is a wee bit bright for lengthy use. It's a great brightness for inspecting something for 5-10 mins, but after that it tends to wear on your eyes, especially for hours of reading on bright-white pages.

// BATTERY
The battery compartment is easy to access without tools, and appears to be a standard sized flat button battery. The LED lights should help it last a long time. Also, be sure to use the on/off switch to help keep the light from turning on accidentally.

// OPERATION
It's a simple push down on the lens ring to turn it on/off. You don't have to touch the lens at all, but it sounds like other reviewers have trouble with that. I feel there is plenty of metal ring around the lens to prevent you form having to touch the lens to turn it on/off.

As I said above, be sure to use the on/off switch to help keep the light from turning on accidentally during storage/travel.

// CONSTRUCTION
I was deeply impressed by the all-metal body of the magnifying glass. And the glass seems to be real glass! Nice. I also really like the grooves that go around the bezel and body. Another nice touch that make using it feel nice in your hand/fingers. Great quality all around.

Note that the battery compartment and switch is plastic.

// GREAT FOR
— kids
— education / classrooms
— people losing the sharpness of their vision
— finding and pulling out splinters
— hobbies and crafts
— electronics

I received a free sample of this product to evaluate and provide an unbiased review.

product_title: Prismacolor Premier Colored Pencils, Soft Core, 24-Count
review_body:
Prismacolor colored pencils are the best colored art pencil available on the market. I have been using these for more than twenty years and have learned so many new ways to use them along the way! I have learned that multiple colors can be easily and smoothly blended together; a textured look can be created by coloring neatly but lightly; a shiny, brilliant finish can be achieved by building up color upon color. I've even heard people talk about applying mineral spirits to the colored areas to help blend and smooth out colors... I have yet to try that technique. When it comes to colored pencils, I would definitely give these a try! You won't be disappointed!

If you are an experienced color blender, this 24-pack has all the colors you will need! I've bought the 24, 48, 72 and 132, and I prefer the smaller pack. I am more tempted to just pick out certain colors and less likely to use cool blending techniques when I have too many options in front of me. For me, when it comes to Prismacolor Pencils, less is more!

product_title: RFID blocking genuine leather wallet for women - Excellent Credit Card Protector for ladies
review_headline: Great for keeping lots of gift or credit cards in - it is made to hold several- I put 20 in mine.
review_body:
Free product provided for evaluation and review.

I love this small, compact wallet and recommended it to my friends. I got the aqua which is a pretty light blue aqua, in a soft pebbled leather. It has metal zippers, 2, that open to 2 different compartments. It has RFID blocking material built into both sizes of the outer walls. The sewing quality of mine is very good to excellent.

It has 15 spaces for cards all together. One side has an accordion type file that has 8 pockets, but you can fit more than one card in, if you like.
I have been using it to keep all my gift cards in. The stick up just a bit at the top so it is easy to see what card is what.

The new proximity readers that read cards can be bought for $10-$20 bucks and work from 10 feet away. It still pays to be careful at checkout when you have a card out, especially if you see someone with a laptop sitting very close by. This wallet will prevent more casual would be thieves that would steal your card info as you walked by though, as long as you keep them in your wallet. I'm bad to use a card then drop it in my purse to replace later, a habit I'm trying to break. Sliding them in this little wallet is easy though, it is helping me break that bad habit.

product_title: HomCom 44" PU leather Adjustable Executive Office Chair w/ Footrest Extension and Back Support - Black
review_headline: Very comfortable in the reclined positions
review_body:
Had the chair for two weeks and it's a love/hate relationship. I was looking for a chair that reclines for those long nights I have to stay over at my Job. And this chair certainly reclines.But as with anything there are pro's and con's. First the Pro's:

Pro's:
--------
- Chair reclines at all different angles and even lays flat. Very comfortable in the reclined positions.
- It has a foot rest that extends out
- It has a adjustable back cushion.
- It supports up to 300lbs

Con's
---------
- The chair back once reclined, does not spring back unless you adjust the recline lever. It does not rock.
- The material that the chair is made of is very grippy. It locks you in the chair. At a reclined position it is a struggle to adjust your self due to the grippyness of the material.
- The seat could use more cushion to it. As the chair is rated for 300lbs I am 290 and it feels like I am bottoming out the seat cushion.
- The foot rest is a little too low when reclined less that 45 degrees. When the chair is laying flat the foot rest is at a perfect height.
- The foot rest feels a little too cheap and flimsy once extended for some one of my size. Time will tell how long it will last with out breaking.

product_title: LotFancy 8GB Digital Voice Recorder MP3 Music Player - Rechargeable Dictaphone with Built-In Speaker, LCD Display, USB Connection
review_headline: Excellent Digital Recorder, Not Many Drawbacks...
review_body:
I have used several digital recorders over the years, mostly from brands like Sony and Olympus, so I was very excited to get to try the [[ASIN:B00AQC5BP6 LotFancy Digital Voice Recorder]] to see if it could stand up to the big boys. The short answer is yes, it can with some cool features other recorders simply don't have. WAV output wasn't a big deal for me so I'm very pleased with this recorder.

Don't be fooled by the entry level price on this recorder, it's actually better than some I have used at triple the price. What I like about having a dedicated personal recorder is it's much easier to share, than say taking recordings on my phone. The portability of this unit and flexibility for use, make it a really great recorder. If I were to accidentally leave it at a business meeting, especially if I have a flight I'm already late for, it's not too expensive to pick up a second one if I never see the first one again.

In terms of function, the recorder keeps most all the necessary buttons on the front and the rest on the sides. Easy press and good responsive feel. The unit is lightweight, so I could keep it in my shirt pocket if needed. There is no excessive learning curve with this recorder; I've had experience with other recorders before, so I picked up on this one really quick. The recorder features a built-in rechargeable battery that is re-powered with a relatively common type mini-USB cable.

More than just a voice recoreder, the unit can also serve as a music player, perfect for killing time just before a business meeting. The package includes a nice pair of ear buds for listening to loaded music, or recordings that have been taken. The recorder also features lots of connectivity, including support for connecting to a phone line for recording business calls, I tested it on a recent call and was so impressed with how easy it worked.

Generally speaking, the [[ASIN:B00AQC5BP6 LotFancy Digital Voice Recorder]] has effectively replaced my big name digital recorders. I love the simple interface, flexibility for use, and all the included accessories I could need. I wish I had a recorder this good years ago.

review_headline: Obi or Google Voice sometimes might not have transmitted all calls, esp. for those automated calls from financial institutions.
review_body:
I have been using OBHAI-Google Voice for a year, recently I found out GV might not have transmitted all calls to me. Especially important ones to mention are those from institutional computing system's phone calls. One that is mostly apparent to me is that calls from CITIBANK FRAUD PREVENTION's Phone system, when they dialed my number to give a critical reference number to unlock my account, attempts of all calls never got thru, and I was never able to get the reference number they need to unlock my credit card account. A couple times I did get the rings and when I picked up to answer, the other end hanged up. Now the CITI credit card is still locked and CITI insists that I have to provide the reference number to unlock my account, regardless how I could persuade them that I could provide all the personal info (eg SSN, secret answers to questions, pin etc).

TO ReneeSD who helped me solved this issue: Thank you so much!! I appreciate your helps and learned the intricate and complexities of GV settings. By the way, the History folder does not has the spam records, I found that CitiBank Fraud Prevention in "SPAM" folder and there they left numerous reference number and messages for me to call. CitiBank Fraud Prevention Number: 423-4676460 is blocked by GV!!

Obi/GV users, are there anybody out there having problems receiving important institutional calls such as the case I described above??

Thank you for all the thoughts given about this because I am thinking to leave GV and to sign up my number with a dedicated VOIP company now !

product_title: Plustek OPTICPRO 12"x17" Large Format 1600dpi Flatbed Scanner - 48 bit Color - 24 bit Grayscale A320
review_body:
Large format scanners are an endangered species. There are not too many choices. Of the top three consumer brands in the market place, the poor buyer is stuck with issues.
.
The Mustek brand has quality problems. Based on user reviews, it arrives DOA or breaks down constantly. The machine is just a useless $200 paper weight.
.
The Epson brand is a quality machine with excellent ratings. At $1,300, it is not affordable.
.
The $500 Plustek Optipro is affordable and is a well-made machine. First, it is light weight. Second, engineers thoughtfully designed it with a top panel of buttons which execute the most common scanner functions. Unfortunately, these attributes are overshadowed by severe software problems. These are detailed below:
.
. . 1. The accompanying CD does not contain the necessary USB 2.0 driver to make the machine work with Windows 7. The user has to download the most recent software from the Plustek website to obtain the necessary driver.
.
. . 2. Instructions on the three accompanying software are bad. The user manual for the Abbyy FineReader 9.0 does not exist. Information on the Doc Action software is very sparse. The user manual for PageManager is very confusing. As a result, the user is forced to \\"play around\\" with the software to get it to work.
.
. . 4. The preview function on the scanning software is useless. The feature is used to make necessary changes to contrast and brightness. When activated a very small image of the scanned page appears. Unfortunately, the image is too small to accurately view the changes. What you see is not what you get.
.
. . 5. After scanning two books, PageManager crashed and refused to save scanned pages. A warning window popped up and said: \\"PageManager is too busy to process this command.\\" Then, everything shut off. Reactivating the program was futile - the software continued to crash. As a result, all three software were uninstalled and reinstalled. This second time around, the USB 2.0 driver was missing despite using the most recent download version.
.
. . 6. The only way to get working again was to resurrect the partition containing the first Plustek installation. This took 30 minutes.
.
.
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
.
.
UPDATE: Day 2
.
I turned on my computer and scanner. A window appeared with this warning: \\"No USB 2.0 Driver Found.\\" Again, I resurrect the partition containing my first Plustek installation. Halfway through my work, the scanner stopped working. A little window exhibited the familiar warning: \\"Pagemanager is too busy to process this command.\\" Then, the software shut off.
.
I resurrected the partition containing my first Plustek installation and was able to continue with my work.
.
.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
.
.
UPDATE: Day 3
.
Day 2 problems were revisited on Day 3.
.
From the above experiences, I notice a trend. Shutting off the scanner or computer corrupts the software.
.
.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
.
.
UPDATE: Day 4
.
Talking with the company's tech support, he advised me to reinstall the software on a virgin Windows 7 boot partition, install a 600 watt power supply in my computer, and unplug all other USB 2.0 devices. These were done, and the familiar problems continued.
.
The entire experience wasted 12 hours of my time. Adding insult to injury, I had to pay $75 in shipping costs.ems continued.
.
The entire experience wasted 12 hours of my time. Adding insult to injury, I had to pay $75 in shipping costs.
