product_title: Canon LBP6030W Wireless Monochrome Printer
review_headline: Works on our Mac OS X Yosemite
review_body:
I just installed this printer and it works. I plugged it into our desktop iMac OS X Yosemite 10.10.2. The printer includes a set up disc, but it is for pc, so you will want to go to us.canon.com to download the driver for Mac. It was easy. They offer 2 different ones, I downloaded and installed both. Then go into your computer, system preferences > printers & scanners > + (add printer). It will see the printer as long as you are plugged in and the power is on, then name it and select software from the dropdown.

The printer included power cable, printer to computer cable and a toner cartridge.

It must have been on sale, we paid $49.99 for this printer. Good buy, no complaints. It's a typical single color black laser printer. We use it for printing text documents and tickets and directions, so I can't comment on the quality of the printer for images. I haven't set it up wirelessly, we don't need to since it shares the desk with our desktop and we have a NAS, so we can keep it simple. Bottom line, if you're a mac user, this printer works on macs.

product_title: Fisher Space Pen Bullet Chrome Finish, Gift Boxed
review_headline: Tip: Rubber Grommet keeps it in your pocket.
review_body:
So yeah, problem is these little guys are escape artists if you're carrying them in your pants pocket. They're so smooth-sided they slip out and disappear. Really annoying.

I'm here to share a tip I've discovered that fixes this problem. Might not be best for everyone, but it's worked REALLY well for me, and it was a cheap/easy thing to do.

I added a rubber grommet around the pen itself. It cost me about a buck at a local hardware store. The rubber "ring" provides a nice amount of grippyness to the inside of the pocket, and the pen ends up not sliding around. It's also positioned where it doesn't get in the way of writing. I'll attach a couple pics.

product_title: Mont Blanc Meisterstuck Le Grand Platinum Ballpoint Pen, 7569
review_headline: An Overall Great Pen with Excellent Weight and Balance.
review_body:
<!DOCTYPE html>. <html> <body> The Mont Blanc Meisterstuck is an iconic pen known around the world. But is it worth the price? I think it all depends on user preferences. Here are my observations and opinions. Pros: Excellent weight and balance. Weight and balance this good is almost impossible to find in any ballpoint pen, at any price-point. Most ballpoint pens are just too weighty towards the top-cap to comfortably write with for prolonged periods of time. The LeGrand feels light, but substantial. Comfortable to use for extended writing periods. Again, the width, combined with the weight and balance, is just right. The included broad black refill is very dark, smooth and long lasting. A comparable refill in terms of line darkness and smoothness, is the Schneider Slider XL. The ink is sometimes dry upon start-up, probably due to remaining dried ink on the exposed ball tip; the ink become quickly usable, given the writing medium, is placed on a suitable and relatively hard surface. Smooth twist mechanism. The twist mechanism is a passive-like device, unlike the Pelikan 600 ballpoint, which actively retracts upon activation. The Mont Blanc must be fully turned in both directions to complete either projection or retraction. My thoughts of this is that the mechanism should be very durable over the long run, since no spring-like mechanism exist. Simple and conservative styling. The pen itself is not distracting and is enjoyable to use, allowing you to focus on studying and taking notes. Some people mention Mont Blanc's "status" quality. Regardless of the brand, this is the most comfortable and ergonomic pen in which I know. Robust and Solid clip. Cons: Ridiculous price point. Mont Blanc's competitive advantage for the LeGrand ball-pen, in my opinion, is the excellent weight and balance. Uncertainties Only time will tell regarding overall durability. Reports have been noted of cracks in the resin. The pen does feel fragile with an almost glass-like quality. It is relatively light, given its size, so the wall thickness must be thin (a trade-off for having a large and light pen). This may be why there are reports cracks in the resin. I do feel that care must be taken to not drop the pen, as would be, with any expensive pen.

product_title: Poweradd Tempered Glass Screen Protector for Microsoft Surface 3 10.8 Inch, HD Clear and Anti-Scratch, Bubble Free and Fingerprint Resistant - Retail Packaging
review_body:
This Screen Protector for the Surface 3 is fantastic! My brother in law is super tech savvy and he always gets the newest gadgets, as soon as they come out. I thought this would provide excellent protection for his investment, so I had to get it for him.

It comes in a binder, which reminds me of a hard bound book. The presentation of the product is top notch! There are very precise and simple instructions to insure proper installation, and it only took him a matter of minutes to apply it. It absolutely holds up to scratches and water spills. He didn't want to drop it to find out how well it prevents the screen from shattering, but I don't blame him!

If you are looking for a great, tempered glass screen protector for your Surface 3, I believe you will be very happy with this product. He's had it on for a couple of weeks now, and hasn't had a single issue. I am so glad I was given the opportunity to receive this, at a great promotional price, in exchange for my honest, unbiased opinion and feedback. He gives this 5 stars, without hesitation.

product_title: Lamy Safari 2014 Special Edition - Neon Coral Extra Fine Point Fountain Pen - L41-EF
review_body: I'd had this on my wishlist and recently got this as a gift and absolutely completely fell in love with this pen. My only other experience with a fountain pen was a Levenger True Writer Kyoto that I'd splurged on a while ago and found difficult to use (in retrospect it probably just needed tuning, or else maybe I just got a poor nib). While that is truly a gorgeous pen, it hasn't gotten much use. Thanks to SREBrown you-tube videos I came to understand that is not a normal first experience and decided to give it another go with this gorgeous baby! I absolutely adore everything about this pen. This color is sooo pretty! Not really coral but not a true pink....pairs well with pink ink tho!  I LOVE the weight (lighter than my heavy resin Levenger), it's extremely easy to hold. Not always an issue but for someone with a history of tendonitis as I do it's a factor for me.  I received this with a converter and immediately filled it with the only bottled ink I had: Levenger - Pinkly. I immediately started using it on printer paper, my planner (Hamermill 32 lb paper) and anything else I could think of. It writes like a dream! Smooth, great flow, not too wet, consistent without skipping. I favor the EF nib compared to the Fine but use both.  Get this pen you will love it!

review_body:
Is there any better satisfaction than slamming down the phone when telemarketers call you at 7 PM?
NO??
You have NOT LIVED until you do.
For you kids in the world, this is a LAND LINE PHONE. Like the one that hangs on your great-grandmother's wall. Like the one on the desk in the school nurse's office, or the assistant principal's office, if they haven't upgraded the school's phones.
Pick this bad boy up off the cradle and dial those 1-900 numbers until your fingernails are stumps.
Call in to QVC and harass the operators who are perpetually "standing by!!"
Then when your call can't be completed as dialed......well.....SLAM THAT BAD BOY DOWN!!!!!!!!!
Don't cheat yourself from the pleasure of dialing while holding the handset under your shoulder...ORDER THIS PHONE!!!
DON'T WAIT, CALL NOW!!!!!

review_body:
Well I don't use this particular printer a whole lot, but upon installing this cartridge, it printed a faint black line lengthwise on the paper about a 1/4" from the edge - barely noticeable - when I first received it. Didn't see anything on the drum, so I figured it would work itself out or settle in. Another 100 pages in, I've got a nice sharp dark line on the prints. And now there is a distinct scratch/groove around the drum in that spot. Guess what...It didn't work itself out. Return period has run out, but the price was right.

Printer also complained regularly about this cartridge not being an OEM. It's the only one that has done that with this or any of my printers.

product_title: VARIDESK - Height-Adjustable Standing Desk - Pro Plus 36
review_headline: Pros and Cons as I see it...
review_body:
Pros:
- Very solid/sturdy construction
- Comes already assembled
- Extremely easy to raise/lower
- Price seems reasonable compared to similar alternatives

Cons:
- Not made for tall people. If you are above 5' 10" and have it placed on a normal height 28" desk, you might find that it is too low - both the keyboard/mouse and monitors. I am 5' 9" and it is the perfect height for me when I extend it to the max height. It doesn't work well ergonomically for my taller colleagues - they would need a taller desk.
- Keyboard/mouse tray does not adjust independently from the monitor shelf. Not a problem if your monitor stands can go fairly high - just adjust the keyboard/mouse tray to the desired height and raise the monitor stands as high as needed. But if your monitors stands don't go very high it could potentially be an issue or you may need to by different stands for monitors or prop them up. I would prefer my monitors a bit higher even though I have the Varidesk extended to the max.

product_title: HP LaserJet Pro Wireless Monochrome Printer
review_headline: Don't even try to use it as a Google Cloud printer
review_body:
EDIT Dec 13, 2015
I replaced this printer with a Brother HL-L2340DW. Very simple to set up, instantly working with Google Cloud Print with pages printing within 10 seconds of command. A much better option for use with Chromebooks. [[ASIN:B00LZS5EEI Brother HL-L2340DW Compact Laser Printer, Monochrome, Wireless, Duplex Printing]]

========

I bought this printer (not from Amazon) for the express purpose of adding print capability to my Chromebox computer system. HP claims that this ability is supported via their HP ePrint service.

First impressions were that the printer is very compact and lightweight. Lightweight as in it felt flimsy but that's not always a good indicator as to how a device will function.

I installed the software as per the HP instructions on a Windows 7 laptop and, after finding my way through the very confusing setup process, had the printer connected to my network via wifi and could print successfully from the laptop. So far, so good.

I then registered the printer on the HP ePrint service. Essentially, HP provides an email address for each printer and when you print to the cloud, an email is sent to HP who then transmits the output to the printer across the internet. Then, using the email address generated by HP, I set up the printer as a Google Cloud printer from my Chromebox. Okay, not a complicated process but one that HP certainly tried to make as confusing as possible. Luckily I have been in technology for 30+ years so knew what to look for.

Here's where it all turned to you-know-what. While I CAN print to the printer from the Chromebox, Every-Single-Page takes around 4 minutes to get transmitted from HP to the printer through the cloud. The green processing light on the printer flashes seemingly forever before each page is spat out. Yes, I guess I can print using the cloud but it is totally and utterly unworkable in a real life situation.

Naturally, at first I thought it was something I had done, or had failed to do. I assigned a static IP the printer, I reviewed EVERY config option through the built in IP addressable control panel, I updated the printer firmware. Nope, it's not me. It's HP, and to prove it, just visit their support website. Dozens of threads discuss this issue that has been ongoing since 2012 - and HP continues to sell the printer as a Google Cloud ready printer. That's totally unacceptable.

If you Google the phrase "hp1102w slow google cloud" you'll see repeated issues with this printer

Although this is a cheap printer, I had high hopes for it. It is small, quiet and the output is good. If you have a Windows PC it will be just fine and I can recommend it (don't know about Apple products). I would give it 4/5 stars based on my admittedly short experience with it. However, as a Google Cloud printer, don't even try. It's a miserable experience and a miserable failure. There are better products out there - I will likely order a Brother HL-L2340DW as a replacement.I thought it was something I had done, or had failed to do. I assigned a static IP the printer, I reviewed EVERY config option through the built in IP addressable control panel, I updated the printer firmware. Nope, it's not me. It's HP, and to prove it, just visit their support website. Dozens of threads discuss this issue that has been ongoing since 2012 - and HP continues to sell the printer as a Google Cloud ready printer. That's totally unacceptable.

If you Google the phrase "hp1102w slow google cloud" you'll see repeated issues with this printer

Although this is a cheap printer, I had high hopes for it. It is small, quiet and the output is good. If you have a Windows PC it will be just fine and I can recommend it (don't know about Apple products). I would give it 4/5 stars based on my admittedly short experience with it. However, as a Google Cloud printer, don't even try. It's a miserable experience and a miserable failure. There are better products out there - I will likely order a Brother HL-L2340DW as a replacement.

Great value for any artist.

product_title: AT-A-GLANCE Weekly / Monthly Planner / Appointment Book, Plan,Write,Remember, Academic Year, July 2015-June 2016, 7.5 x 10 Inch Page Size (70-7957-05)
review_body:
This is a far nicer planner than I was expecting. The cover is nice and the strap that holds it closed is a good touch. It should help keep things like notes and receipts from falling out.

It has three full year calendars at the beginning, a list of holidays for 15-17, then the pages for the dates. It starts June 29, 2015 and goes to July 3, 2016. Each two page spread has the week in columns, one per day. The day is then broken down by hour, starting at 7am and going to 6:30pm, with more lines for time after that (but they don't have the hours marked). There is room on the side for notes for each week.

At the end there is a two page spread of the month of July 2016, for future planning purposes. Then there are pages for event planning by month and a couple of blank pages for notes and "quick references". I really like the pocket on the back cover. Very handy for small receipts or something that you need to keep with your planner.

We're using this for work/ministry mileage and events. There will be room for meeting notes on the days we have them (since we won't be filling up the entire day with stuff, we hope) for quickly finding out when things were decided and when things are planned.

review_headline: Look good, easy install, tips need to be glued on
review_body: They look good and are very easy to install. One problem is that the tips are not glued on or otherwise attached. They come off easily and we have babies in the house so that's bad. This was easily solved with a hot glue gun. Pro tip: we tried other glues and none worked well at all due to the white coating on the spring and the rubber tip - most glues just don't adhere those things very well. However, hot glue works perfectly - hardens in seconds and holds very fast. I actually sat and watched my 10-month-old as he found one of these installed and tried for 5 minutes to yank the tip off of it to no avail.
